WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.669 --> 00:00:05.838
COMMENTARY:
Hi, I'm Alex Aja, the director.

2
00:00:06.005 --> 00:00:10.176
Hi, I'm Greg Levasseur. I'm the
cowriter and I did the art direction.

3
00:00:10.343 --> 00:00:12.261
This is Marianne Maddalena,
the producer.

4
00:00:12.428 --> 00:00:16.015
One of the three producers,
with Wes Craven and Peter Locke.

5
00:00:16.182 --> 00:00:18.810
And I'm gonna start by saying that,
you know, it's--

6
00:00:18.976 --> 00:00:22.021
We are so proud to have that logo
in the beginning of the movie.

7
00:00:22.188 --> 00:00:25.399
It's like, you know, we are coming
from the low-budget world with--

8
00:00:25.566 --> 00:00:27.693
You know, <i>High Tension</i>
was very low budget...

9
00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:32.490
...and to make a movie
with Fox is amazing. It's great.

10
00:00:33.866 --> 00:00:38.913
So the main idea of remaking
<i>The Hills Have Eyes</i> was to bring...

11
00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:43.126
...that nuclear-testing background based
on the real facts in New Mexico...

12
00:00:43.292 --> 00:00:45.294
...and Nevada desert.

13
00:00:46.712 --> 00:00:48.631
So that scene was like....

14
00:00:48.798 --> 00:00:53.970
That didn't came with the first draft
of the script. It came, like, later...

15
00:00:54.137 --> 00:00:56.681
...because were thinking about--
We need--

16
00:00:56.848 --> 00:00:59.642
As Wes showed
in a few of his movies...

17
00:00:59.809 --> 00:01:04.021
...we need to start the movie
very strongly and very...

18
00:01:04.188 --> 00:01:09.318
...violent and brutal.
And the idea of that sand is like...

19
00:01:09.485 --> 00:01:12.280
...you know, like walking
the area with Geiger counter...

20
00:01:12.446 --> 00:01:16.075
...and being attacked and
massacred by someone like--

21
00:01:16.242 --> 00:01:21.164
By, like, a ominous silhouette
was pretty exciting.

22
00:01:21.330 --> 00:01:23.249
And unfortunately...

23
00:01:23.416 --> 00:01:27.461
...because of the schedule
and because of budget and stuff...

24
00:01:27.628 --> 00:01:29.380
...we were forced...

25
00:01:29.547 --> 00:01:32.425
...to separate ourselves,
and Greg directed the scene.

26
00:01:32.592 --> 00:01:34.010
Unfortunately for Alex...

27
00:01:34.177 --> 00:01:37.513
...he was very disappointed
when I came back and showed him...

28
00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:41.893
...the dailies of this scene. And he was
a little bit pissed off to not participate.

29
00:01:42.059 --> 00:01:43.227
[COMMENTATORS CHUCKLING]

30
00:01:43.394 --> 00:01:46.147
Yeah, it was great, because we--

31
00:01:46.314 --> 00:01:49.650
We... On that picture,
there was a big second unit...

32
00:01:49.817 --> 00:01:51.694
...and Greg directed
like three weeks.

33
00:01:51.861 --> 00:01:55.656
And that scene is the big one,
and it's also the opening one.

34
00:01:55.865 --> 00:01:58.284
And the guy on the screen,
it's also another funny fact...

35
00:01:58.451 --> 00:02:00.786
...is one of our best friends,
he's a French guy.

36
00:02:00.953 --> 00:02:05.666
The first victim, the guy covered with
blood that you saw is, like-- Yeah, it's--

37
00:02:05.833 --> 00:02:07.877
He's our location manager
on the movie.

38
00:02:08.044 --> 00:02:09.712
- Yeah, yeah.
- And your good friend.

39
00:02:09.879 --> 00:02:12.048
And it's-- Yeah, and a very,
very good friend.

40
00:02:12.215 --> 00:02:15.384
So in this scene, you have to
imagine that there is a big crane...

41
00:02:15.551 --> 00:02:20.431
...above the scientist and a cable which
allowed them to be swept into the--

42
00:02:20.598 --> 00:02:25.102
Everything was made with wire and--
So the guy can be hit...

43
00:02:25.436 --> 00:02:27.772
...against the rocks like a rag doll.

44
00:02:27.939 --> 00:02:30.107
It was very funny.
And you have to imagine...

45
00:02:30.274 --> 00:02:33.736
...the stuntmen who did that,
they had been, like...

46
00:02:33.903 --> 00:02:37.657
-...smashed during all the day.
- Yeah, under like 120 degrees.

47
00:02:37.823 --> 00:02:40.493
With a combination--
I mean, the suit of the scientist--

48
00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:43.746
Yeah, with the scientist suit,
which was, like, so hot.

49
00:02:47.541 --> 00:02:51.504
That image, that's a commercial from
the '50s. In fact, it's a short film...

50
00:02:51.671 --> 00:02:54.632
...that I heard David Lynch
is a big fan of that short film...

51
00:02:54.799 --> 00:02:57.468
...because it shows exactly
the kitchen of the future...

52
00:02:57.635 --> 00:03:01.889
...and the idea of how the family...

53
00:03:02.056 --> 00:03:06.686
...was in the U.S. at that time.
And we used the song...

54
00:03:06.852 --> 00:03:09.522
..."More and More."
"More and more I forget my past"...

55
00:03:09.689 --> 00:03:13.067
...mixing with the nuclear-testing
image and footage.

56
00:03:13.234 --> 00:03:17.613
And that brings the movie
in a kind of nostalgic way...

57
00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:22.285
...but in the same time, you see
some awful stuff coming, like flashes...

58
00:03:22.451 --> 00:03:24.578
...inside the opening-title scene.

59
00:03:24.787 --> 00:03:28.708
I went to Paris to see the movie,
the first cut of the movie.

60
00:03:28.874 --> 00:03:31.919
Alex and Greg came up with
this sequence totally on their own...

61
00:03:32.086 --> 00:03:35.006
...with our editor, Baxter.
We were gonna hire a main title--

62
00:03:35.172 --> 00:03:37.842
People to do the main titles,
and they came up with this...

63
00:03:38.009 --> 00:03:39.427
...and found this footage.

64
00:03:39.593 --> 00:03:45.099
Yeah, and all the pictures that you are
watching in the middle of the--

65
00:03:45.266 --> 00:03:47.852
Of the nuclear-testing footage
are from...

66
00:03:48.019 --> 00:03:54.483
...real footage of all the fallout
and all the nuclear fallout.

67
00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:56.694
And the radioactive fallout can--

68
00:03:56.902 --> 00:04:00.031
Can have a big, big influence
on the genetic and the human being.

69
00:04:00.197 --> 00:04:04.660
Everything is real. Everything is based
on Chernobyl kids...

70
00:04:04.827 --> 00:04:07.455
...or Hiroshima kids and also some...

71
00:04:07.621 --> 00:04:11.334
...which is not radioactive,
like Agent Orange effect in Vietnam.

72
00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:14.837
And we based all the makeup
and all the design of the hills dweller...

73
00:04:15.004 --> 00:04:19.342
...based on those pictures
that you can see in the opening title...

74
00:04:19.508 --> 00:04:21.510
-...which are real.
- All the deformities...

75
00:04:21.677 --> 00:04:24.305
...were based on real mutants.

76
00:04:24.472 --> 00:04:29.101
The good thing with
this opening credit, it's...

77
00:04:29.268 --> 00:04:33.105
It's a way to... Not to teach,
but to say to the audience...

78
00:04:33.272 --> 00:04:39.028
...what's really happened and to make,
like, a really short story about...

79
00:04:39.195 --> 00:04:41.155
...the 30 years of testing and stuff.

80
00:04:41.697 --> 00:04:44.784
It's a way to not, like,
giving too much information...

81
00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:48.913
...but in the same time to be sure
that everyone can understand...

82
00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:50.956
...what is the background
of that movie.

83
00:04:51.123 --> 00:04:55.211
And what were the testing
in the desert in the U.S.

84
00:04:55.378 --> 00:04:59.632
And here, it's our tribute to
<i>Once Upon a Time in the West</i>.

85
00:04:59.799 --> 00:05:02.676
I mean, I remember talking
from the beginning...

86
00:05:02.843 --> 00:05:07.848
...with Joseph Nemec, the production
designer, and we bring him a lot...

87
00:05:08.015 --> 00:05:11.894
...of reference picture
and reference images...

88
00:05:12.061 --> 00:05:14.605
...of gas stations in the desert
and all the details.

89
00:05:14.772 --> 00:05:17.900
And we bring, like, tons of details
that we wanted to see.

90
00:05:18.067 --> 00:05:22.696
And he managed to bring everything
and to build, like, this...

91
00:05:22.863 --> 00:05:25.533
...gas station in the middle
of the desert in Morocco...

92
00:05:25.699 --> 00:05:28.202
...because we shot the movie
in Morocco. Ouarzazate.

93
00:05:28.369 --> 00:05:32.206
And the action is supposedly
to take place in New Mexico.

94
00:05:32.373 --> 00:05:38.337
And he managed to build
that exactly American location.

95
00:05:38.504 --> 00:05:42.258
And it's not a Western,
but it's open like a Western.

96
00:05:42.425 --> 00:05:47.430
It opens, like, very silent with the
"crink-cronk" of the water wheel.

97
00:05:47.596 --> 00:05:51.892
And there is a kind of mystery.
It was like nobody--

98
00:05:52.059 --> 00:05:55.187
I mean, everyone wasn't convinced
that that scene...

99
00:05:55.354 --> 00:05:57.898
...was necessary in the movie.

100
00:05:58.065 --> 00:06:01.902
But for us, it was a way to enter.
Even if we're not following the lead actor...

101
00:06:02.069 --> 00:06:03.988
...or the lead character of the movie...

102
00:06:04.155 --> 00:06:08.826
...it's a way to enter the world
of <i>The Hills Have Eyes</i>.

103
00:06:08.993 --> 00:06:13.622
And it has him walking around the gas
station and walking towards the fence.

104
00:06:13.789 --> 00:06:18.586
Behind which
there is the radioactive...

105
00:06:18.752 --> 00:06:20.629
...testing area.

106
00:06:23.507 --> 00:06:27.011
We went-- First unit
went to do that shot...

107
00:06:27.178 --> 00:06:31.474
...and the wind was, like, so strong
and the crane was not working...

108
00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:35.311
...and second unit came back and
did that amazing, amazing shot.

109
00:06:35.478 --> 00:06:38.189
It's one of my favorite shots
of the movie that Greg did.

110
00:06:38.355 --> 00:06:41.484
- I mean, it's amazing.
- Yeah, but it was easier to do it...

111
00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:44.904
...after-- When you got the reference
of the first shot.

112
00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:47.948
After you know what you
can improve on the shot.

113
00:06:48.115 --> 00:06:50.242
Yeah, and to manage
to have that scorpion...

114
00:06:50.409 --> 00:06:51.994
...like, walking on the rocks...

115
00:06:52.161 --> 00:06:53.871
You have to imagine
there is a guy...

116
00:06:54.038 --> 00:06:58.501
...you know, hidden behind the rock
who frees the scorpion.

117
00:06:58.876 --> 00:07:01.879
And that place is not built.
In fact, we found that location...

118
00:07:02.046 --> 00:07:05.549
...that exact mine-entrance location,
in Morocco.

119
00:07:05.716 --> 00:07:09.762
With even, like--
What's the name of the little chariot--?

120
00:07:09.929 --> 00:07:13.265
- Not the mine shaft, but the--
- Yeah, everything was really here.

121
00:07:13.432 --> 00:07:16.393
It was all found. Everything--
We found everything just there.

122
00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:20.940
And it's so real. It's exactly the kind of
mine that you can find in New Mexico.

123
00:07:22.233 --> 00:07:24.068
Now, this gas station
still stands in Morocco.

124
00:07:24.235 --> 00:07:25.903
Yeah, I think they didn't touch it.

125
00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:28.822
And it's on the road of Agadir,
which is another town.

126
00:07:28.989 --> 00:07:32.409
You know, we went really all around
the world to find...

127
00:07:32.576 --> 00:07:37.540
...the best location possible because,
once again, it's <i>The Hills Have Eyes</i>.

128
00:07:37.706 --> 00:07:39.959
So the hills are like
one of the lead actor...

129
00:07:40.125 --> 00:07:42.628
...even like one of the lead
character of the movie.

130
00:07:42.795 --> 00:07:44.922
Even maybe, like, the lead bad guy.

131
00:07:45.089 --> 00:07:49.134
And everywhere, like--
It were, like, nice places...

132
00:07:49.301 --> 00:07:52.763
...but nothing compared to
what Morocco can provide.

133
00:07:52.930 --> 00:07:56.475
What Morocco provides, it's exactly
what you can find in New Mexico...

134
00:07:56.642 --> 00:07:58.978
...but bigger and...

135
00:07:59.144 --> 00:08:02.189
...even, like, more ominous
and more jagged and more....

136
00:08:02.356 --> 00:08:05.818
More original.
Nobody shot where we shot.

137
00:08:05.985 --> 00:08:08.404
And it's funny because
during the prep, we mixed...

138
00:08:08.571 --> 00:08:11.365
...some picture of New Mexico
and Morocco and nobody...

139
00:08:11.532 --> 00:08:14.535
...could be able to make
the difference between the--

140
00:08:14.702 --> 00:08:17.121
- Both of them.
- Yeah, both of them.

141
00:08:19.248 --> 00:08:22.918
So it was a big challenge for Joseph
Nemec, the production designer, to....

142
00:08:23.085 --> 00:08:27.089
To bring that feeling of....

143
00:08:27.256 --> 00:08:32.303
That so strong feeling of U.S. here
in the desert in Morocco, of course.

144
00:08:32.469 --> 00:08:35.431
And, you know, I think it's....

145
00:08:35.598 --> 00:08:39.059
After that scene, you don't
even wonder where it's taking place.

146
00:08:39.226 --> 00:08:41.979
It's taking place in New Mexico
around, like, Santa Fe.

147
00:08:42.146 --> 00:08:43.480
It's true, you can--

148
00:08:43.647 --> 00:08:46.233
Around Santa Fe,
you can find the same kind of colors...

149
00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:50.362
...the same kind of vegetation, exactly
the same kind of hills, mountain...

150
00:08:50.696 --> 00:08:54.867
...canyon. It's the same geology, exactly.

151
00:08:55.034 --> 00:08:57.870
And when we were
writing the script...

152
00:08:58.037 --> 00:09:01.790
...we decided to keep that idea of
starting with a character...

153
00:09:01.957 --> 00:09:07.254
...like the gas-station attendant
and then having the Carter family...

154
00:09:07.421 --> 00:09:10.341
...stop by to pour some gas.

155
00:09:10.507 --> 00:09:12.635
And that's very interesting
because in--

156
00:09:12.801 --> 00:09:16.347
The obvious way to make
that kind of movie is to start...

157
00:09:16.513 --> 00:09:19.975
...the story with them in the car
and following them to the gas station.

158
00:09:20.142 --> 00:09:24.813
Here it's the opposite.
You present all the character...

159
00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.524
...in one scene,
which is not so easy to do.

160
00:09:27.733 --> 00:09:30.402
And it's another way to tell the story.

161
00:09:30.569 --> 00:09:34.156
And it's very interesting because nobody
knows who is going to follow them.

162
00:09:34.323 --> 00:09:35.491
That was a tricky part...

163
00:09:35.658 --> 00:09:39.203
...because you have to present
very quickly seven characters...

164
00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:41.914
...in the same time and so....

165
00:09:42.081 --> 00:09:46.251
Yeah, and all the relationships
between them, you know?

166
00:09:46.418 --> 00:09:49.630
Because the idea was to try
to develop all the characters...

167
00:09:49.838 --> 00:09:52.174
...and to make them exist
and to understand them.

168
00:09:52.341 --> 00:09:55.678
Because the more you feel for them,
the more you will scare for them also.

169
00:09:55.844 --> 00:09:59.848
DOUG: Your parents can't stand me.
- No, you're wrong. They love you.

170
00:10:00.015 --> 00:10:01.850
I could have taken them on a cruise.

171
00:10:02.059 --> 00:10:03.102
You know what? Stop.

172
00:10:03.268 --> 00:10:06.980
COMMENTARY: So shooting in
a trailer is pretty, pretty hard.

173
00:10:07.147 --> 00:10:10.150
So the only way, because--
Even an Airstream is very small.

174
00:10:10.317 --> 00:10:15.531
So we rebuilt the trailer,
the Airstream trailer, on-stage...

175
00:10:15.698 --> 00:10:20.077
...and we asked Joseph Nemec
to build the same exact trailer...

176
00:10:20.244 --> 00:10:22.496
...but, like, 30 percent bigger.

177
00:10:22.663 --> 00:10:27.084
So it was more easy for us to move
with the camera and shoot inside.

178
00:10:27.501 --> 00:10:32.089
At the same time, you have to take care
to not show that the trailer is bigger...

179
00:10:32.297 --> 00:10:34.550
...so that was also a little bit tricky.

180
00:10:34.717 --> 00:10:38.595
Yeah, but even me, like, you know,
after making the movie...

181
00:10:38.762 --> 00:10:42.307
...I just forgot that everything
wasn't made in the same time.

182
00:10:42.474 --> 00:10:45.436
For me, they are inside,
like, trying to fix the a.c.

183
00:10:45.602 --> 00:10:47.813
Well, also, the air conditioning
on the stage...

184
00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:50.190
...and inside the trailer
wasn't working.

185
00:10:50.399 --> 00:10:52.443
So it was hotter inside than outside.

186
00:10:52.609 --> 00:10:54.737
It was about 130 degrees
inside that trailer.

187
00:10:54.903 --> 00:10:57.531
Yeah, even when we were on-stage,
it was, like, so hot.

188
00:10:57.698 --> 00:11:01.034
I mean, you know, it's common sense.
You don't shoot in the desert...

189
00:11:01.201 --> 00:11:03.120
...during July-August.

190
00:11:03.287 --> 00:11:06.123
And because of production reasons,
and many reasons...

191
00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:11.837
...the shooting was delayed to exactly
July-August in the Sahara desert.

192
00:11:12.004 --> 00:11:14.339
Which is pretty hot.

193
00:11:14.506 --> 00:11:17.718
Pretty hot, and sandstorm every day.

194
00:11:17.885 --> 00:11:20.137
- Every day at the same time.
- Three o'clock.

195
00:11:20.304 --> 00:11:22.765
Yeah, 3:00, sandstorm.

196
00:11:22.931 --> 00:11:24.767
- So that was--
- It was brutal. Hot.

197
00:11:24.933 --> 00:11:28.187
- It was really hot and brutal, yeah.
- Six days a week.

198
00:11:28.353 --> 00:11:31.064
The other tricky part,
and it's the same in New Mexico...

199
00:11:31.231 --> 00:11:35.861
...is the color of the hills. It's so
different. You can find pink, red...

200
00:11:36.028 --> 00:11:39.823
...yellow, ochre. I mean, you can really
find all the different kind of colors.

201
00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:41.992
And for the DP, it's a big challenge.

202
00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:45.037
And I think Maxime Alexandre,
our DP...

203
00:11:45.245 --> 00:11:47.706
...did, like, an amazing job,
because he managed...

204
00:11:47.873 --> 00:11:51.251
...to make everything look not the same,
but belong to the same place...

205
00:11:51.418 --> 00:11:54.671
...even if we are not shooting
exactly in the same place each time.

206
00:11:58.425 --> 00:12:01.929
And behind the trailer,
you can see in the distance...

207
00:12:02.095 --> 00:12:07.351
...some remains of another location
built for another movie.

208
00:12:07.518 --> 00:12:09.853
For, like, an Italian TV show...

209
00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:13.232
...like, years ago, they didn't touch
also on the road to Morocco.

210
00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:16.735
So I guess in a few years,
in Ouarzazate, on that road...

211
00:12:16.902 --> 00:12:18.737
...coming from Ouarzazate to Agadir...

212
00:12:18.904 --> 00:12:21.532
...you'll find different location
from different movie.

213
00:12:21.698 --> 00:12:25.244
It's going to be like
a little Hollywood in the desert.

214
00:12:25.744 --> 00:12:28.038
BOBBY:
Thanks, Brenda.

215
00:12:28.539 --> 00:12:31.625
COMMENTARY:
That's, like, some chicken meat with fly...

216
00:12:31.792 --> 00:12:33.043
...and everything was real.

217
00:12:33.210 --> 00:12:35.504
So you have to imagine
after two days--

218
00:12:35.712 --> 00:12:38.006
Yeah, the smell. The smell was awful.

219
00:12:38.173 --> 00:12:41.552
It was just impossible to come, like...

220
00:12:41.718 --> 00:12:45.556
- That was so disgusting.
-...less than 5 meters from the outhouse.

221
00:12:45.722 --> 00:12:47.266
Yeah.

222
00:12:48.016 --> 00:12:50.686
Talk about this baby.
How did we find her?

223
00:12:50.853 --> 00:12:51.979
The baby save us.

224
00:12:52.145 --> 00:12:56.024
Without Maisie, the baby,
the little girl, we'd be dead.

225
00:12:56.191 --> 00:12:59.611
Maisie comes from Malta. We searched
everywhere for the right baby.

226
00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:03.115
We couldn't find a baby that
matched the family in Morocco.

227
00:13:03.323 --> 00:13:06.994
Yeah, it was impossible. And it was very
hard, also, to bring a baby from U.S.

228
00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:09.997
And because of the heat, the desert,
the condition...

229
00:13:10.163 --> 00:13:16.128
...it was so, so difficult.
So we were lucky that...

230
00:13:16.336 --> 00:13:20.340
...one crew member have, like, her best
friend coming on vacation in Morocco...

231
00:13:20.507 --> 00:13:24.761
...and bring the baby and the parents--
The parents accept--

232
00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:28.015
Agree on letting their daughter,
which was like...

233
00:13:28.181 --> 00:13:30.642
-...she was 6 months old--
- Yeah, 6 months old...

234
00:13:30.851 --> 00:13:34.730
-...work in the desert.
- Yeah, usually on movie, they--

235
00:13:34.897 --> 00:13:36.398
Usually on movies, they....

236
00:13:36.565 --> 00:13:38.400
- You find twins.
- Yeah, you find twins.

237
00:13:38.567 --> 00:13:42.362
And that was the case.
And she was so good. Maisie is--

238
00:13:42.529 --> 00:13:45.073
- She is amazing.
- She was just a doll. She was a gem.

239
00:13:45.240 --> 00:13:47.951
She was so good,
her acting was wonderful...

240
00:13:48.118 --> 00:13:50.120
...she was never grouchy,
she never cried.

241
00:13:50.287 --> 00:13:51.788
Exactly. It was, like, amazing.

242
00:13:51.955 --> 00:13:54.583
And everyone was
so in love with her on set.

243
00:13:54.750 --> 00:13:57.878
She was like-- She really
brings something to the movie.

244
00:13:58.045 --> 00:14:01.089
She brings a very strong reason
for the quest at the end.

245
00:14:01.256 --> 00:14:04.593
You really care for her.
It's-- She's amazing.

246
00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:08.013
She's amazing. I'm really looking
forward to the day where...

247
00:14:08.180 --> 00:14:11.308
...a young girl is going to come and say,
"You know what? I was the baby...

248
00:14:11.475 --> 00:14:14.895
...in <i>The Hills Have Eyes</i>."
I'm sure it's going to happen.

249
00:14:16.313 --> 00:14:19.650
We had a great time with her parents.
They were really good troupers.

250
00:14:19.816 --> 00:14:22.569
- And we all had a great time on the set.
- Yeah.

251
00:14:24.029 --> 00:14:26.531
But, I mean, the baby is one thing...

252
00:14:26.698 --> 00:14:29.076
...but all the cast
on that movie were, like....

253
00:14:29.743 --> 00:14:31.411
It was very-- It was a long run...

254
00:14:31.578 --> 00:14:34.748
...it was a long process to find
everyone and to be sure...

255
00:14:34.915 --> 00:14:38.168
...that everyone was able
to play so extreme situation.

256
00:14:38.335 --> 00:14:42.172
But, you know, being in Morocco
with them and being in...

257
00:14:42.381 --> 00:14:46.551
...a kind of survival condition,
as they are in the movie...

258
00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:49.846
...showed that we
were exactly correct.

259
00:14:50.013 --> 00:14:51.723
I mean, everyone's great.

260
00:14:51.890 --> 00:14:53.850
We were stuck
in the middle of nowhere.

261
00:14:54.017 --> 00:14:56.728
And we worked six days a week
and we had one hotel.

262
00:14:56.895 --> 00:14:59.523
And we basically hung out
with each other all the time.

263
00:14:59.690 --> 00:15:01.483
- And we survived.
- And we survived.

264
00:15:03.568 --> 00:15:05.070
- Ted Levine.
- Yeah.

265
00:15:05.737 --> 00:15:07.864
- Kathleen.
- Kathleen Quinlan.

266
00:15:08.031 --> 00:15:10.158
And we got Vinessa Shaw.

267
00:15:10.325 --> 00:15:14.454
And I mean, you know,
Aaron and Dan are, like, amazing.

268
00:15:14.621 --> 00:15:18.917
I mean, you know, everyone is great.
And all the hills dweller also...

269
00:15:19.084 --> 00:15:22.879
...are very, very impressive because
they are, like, also acting...

270
00:15:23.046 --> 00:15:24.589
...with prosthetics and makeup.

271
00:15:24.798 --> 00:15:28.844
And they're like, 100 degrees
and 120 degrees sometimes...

272
00:15:29.011 --> 00:15:32.139
...which is, like--
Make the makeup melt.

273
00:15:33.473 --> 00:15:35.684
BOB: Yeah?
- You know...

274
00:15:35.934 --> 00:15:36.977
...it's not on--

275
00:15:37.144 --> 00:15:38.895
COMMENTARY: This is Tom Bower.
- Yeah.

276
00:15:39.104 --> 00:15:42.524
Great job as the gas-station attendant.
Wonderful actor.

277
00:15:43.275 --> 00:15:45.944
And also, the heat of the place
where we were shooting...

278
00:15:46.111 --> 00:15:47.946
...is also not so easy
for the light...

279
00:15:48.113 --> 00:15:52.492
...because the heat changed the light.
When it's too hot, it became, like...

280
00:15:52.659 --> 00:15:56.747
...impossible to see the horizon
or to see-- It become very hazy.

281
00:15:56.955 --> 00:15:59.875
So that's why also we decided
to do a lot of split days...

282
00:16:00.042 --> 00:16:01.668
...which was not so easy.

283
00:16:01.835 --> 00:16:04.629
Because we were, like,
shooting afternoon and then night.

284
00:16:04.796 --> 00:16:07.591
Going against the continuity
of the movie and the script--

285
00:16:07.758 --> 00:16:11.303
So that was a big challenge. Everything
was a big challenge on that movie.

286
00:16:11.470 --> 00:16:14.139
Particularly on this shot,
because this shot, we got--

287
00:16:14.306 --> 00:16:16.767
So once again, the crane broke...

288
00:16:16.933 --> 00:16:19.603
...so we were supposed to have
a big crane shot, like...

289
00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:21.480
...leading to that point of view...

290
00:16:21.646 --> 00:16:24.941
...and then crane down
on the gas-station guy...

291
00:16:25.150 --> 00:16:26.610
...watching them go and--

292
00:16:26.777 --> 00:16:31.114
Just broken, and the sun was, like,
setting behind the hill, so it was like....

293
00:16:31.281 --> 00:16:34.367
We were, like, 15 minutes
before night...

294
00:16:34.534 --> 00:16:37.621
...and the next day we have
to move to another place.

295
00:16:37.788 --> 00:16:42.876
So we did that traveling shot,
that pulling on him--

296
00:16:43.043 --> 00:16:44.544
That pushing on him.

297
00:16:44.878 --> 00:16:46.171
--And it was only one take.

298
00:16:46.338 --> 00:16:47.380
Yeah, only one take...

299
00:16:47.547 --> 00:16:50.801
...because it was very difficult
for the trailer to make a U-turn...

300
00:16:50.967 --> 00:16:53.470
-...so they need, like, 20 minutes to--
- To get back.

301
00:16:53.637 --> 00:16:56.807
So it was really, like, one shot,
one opportunity.

302
00:17:00.602 --> 00:17:04.606
That was supposed to be
the first binoculars POV...

303
00:17:04.773 --> 00:17:08.860
...from the hills on the trailer arriving.

304
00:17:09.027 --> 00:17:12.739
And in the editing room,
we decided to stay....

305
00:17:12.906 --> 00:17:15.200
You know, to not imply
the binoculars yet.

306
00:17:15.367 --> 00:17:18.411
But, in fact, we got a lot of shots
of the trailer passing by...

307
00:17:18.578 --> 00:17:22.415
...and going to this pass.
And during the editing...

308
00:17:22.582 --> 00:17:25.127
...we realized that it was impossible
to have this--

309
00:17:25.293 --> 00:17:28.130
- To use everything.
- To use everything of this long trip.

310
00:17:30.215 --> 00:17:33.927
That-- All that scene
was made in different--

311
00:17:34.136 --> 00:17:36.847
Like, in one hand,
we used the poor-man process...

312
00:17:37.013 --> 00:17:42.894
...which is like, basically, some grips
moving the car with a wind machine.

313
00:17:43.103 --> 00:17:46.898
But that specific part of the scene,
when they're on the road...

314
00:17:47.107 --> 00:17:52.654
...and Ted was really driving the car
with the genny on the hood of the car...

315
00:17:52.821 --> 00:17:56.658
...and he was also doing the....
Slight?

316
00:17:57.033 --> 00:17:59.661
- The slate? Yeah, the slate.
- The clacker, the slate.

317
00:17:59.828 --> 00:18:01.163
Himself, with two cameras.

318
00:18:01.329 --> 00:18:03.707
But on each side of the road,
there is a canyon...

319
00:18:03.874 --> 00:18:06.835
...so it was, like, pretty dangerous,
and he was so good.

320
00:18:07.002 --> 00:18:09.254
And we are lucky.
And if you watch carefully...

321
00:18:09.421 --> 00:18:12.716
...it's funny because the sun is setting
on both sides of the car.

322
00:18:13.133 --> 00:18:17.470
So it's funny. You don't feel that,
but you can really see it.

323
00:18:17.637 --> 00:18:22.267
Here it's a good example of
how to shoot on-stage...

324
00:18:22.434 --> 00:18:26.229
...and feeling that you are also outside.
Of course, we are on-stage here...

325
00:18:26.396 --> 00:18:29.232
...and what you saw by the window
was made by second unit...

326
00:18:29.399 --> 00:18:33.528
...and then add in CGI
by Jamison Goei.

327
00:18:34.487 --> 00:18:37.449
And so you have the feeling that
you are, like, on the road...

328
00:18:37.616 --> 00:18:43.246
...and it sold the idea of
the trailer being the real trailer.

329
00:18:43.997 --> 00:18:48.001
BOBBY:
There. It's just the thermostat.

330
00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:51.755
- It was disconnected.
- Anyway...

331
00:18:51.922 --> 00:18:54.007
...at least we can breathe now.

332
00:18:58.345 --> 00:19:01.223
Hey, I thought you quit smoking.

333
00:19:01.431 --> 00:19:02.849
Does my sister know?

334
00:19:03.016 --> 00:19:06.895
COMMENTARY: I love the dynamic
between Doug and Bobby.

335
00:19:07.103 --> 00:19:13.026
You really feel that Bobby is torn
between his vision of his father...

336
00:19:13.193 --> 00:19:16.154
...which is like the....
You know, the patriarchal figure...

337
00:19:16.321 --> 00:19:18.990
...the father figure,
the Republican figure...

338
00:19:19.157 --> 00:19:22.869
...and his brother-in-law, which is
the cool guy, a little bit coward.

339
00:19:23.078 --> 00:19:27.457
And he really doesn't know yet
who's going to-- Who he wants to be.

340
00:19:27.624 --> 00:19:29.584
DOUG:
--would cut my nuts off if you started.

341
00:19:29.751 --> 00:19:32.629
I think she did that a long time ago.

342
00:19:32.796 --> 00:19:34.464
I think you're right.

343
00:19:36.299 --> 00:19:37.342
COMMENTARY:
The place.

344
00:19:37.509 --> 00:19:39.928
I mean, I remember the first time
we arrived on that road...

345
00:19:40.095 --> 00:19:44.891
...which is an old mining road
closed for years now in Morocco.

346
00:19:45.058 --> 00:19:47.560
And we found the place
and we had the feeling...

347
00:19:47.727 --> 00:19:50.230
-...that it was waiting for us.
- The funny thing...

348
00:19:50.397 --> 00:19:52.732
...that the first place,
in fact, that we found.

349
00:19:52.899 --> 00:19:54.609
We came from Marrakech...

350
00:19:54.776 --> 00:19:56.820
...and 50 kilometers
before Ouarzazate...

351
00:19:56.987 --> 00:20:00.532
...we say, "Now we can start to scout."
And that's the place that we found.

352
00:20:00.699 --> 00:20:03.910
Yeah, and nobody shot before here,
and it's so perfect.

353
00:20:04.077 --> 00:20:08.873
It's 360 degrees of nothing,
no civilization, no town...

354
00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:13.628
...nothing built, just hills
and rocks and canyon.

355
00:20:13.795 --> 00:20:15.839
And it's amazing.
And when we came back...

356
00:20:16.006 --> 00:20:21.136
...like, for the following scouting,
we found all the canyon behind...

357
00:20:21.303 --> 00:20:24.014
...and we found, like,
places that we use in the movie...

358
00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:28.018
...when he's looking for the dog
and when they are fighting at the end.

359
00:20:28.184 --> 00:20:30.520
And everything was there,
really waiting for us.

360
00:20:30.729 --> 00:20:35.567
Like, you can walk from a set
to the other one.

361
00:20:35.734 --> 00:20:38.361
It's amazing.
It's full of rattlesnakes.

362
00:20:38.528 --> 00:20:42.866
Not rattlesnakes, but full of
scorpions and desert snakes.

363
00:20:43.033 --> 00:20:44.868
Cedric did a great job with that stunt.

364
00:20:45.035 --> 00:20:47.120
- Our stunt coordinator.
- Yeah, yeah, Cedric.

365
00:20:47.287 --> 00:20:48.955
- First time.
- First time, exactly.

366
00:20:49.122 --> 00:20:51.541
- First-time stunt coordinator.
- Going way too fast.

367
00:20:51.708 --> 00:20:53.543
- But that's great.
- Exactly, it worked.

368
00:20:53.710 --> 00:20:54.878
On-screen, it's amazing.

369
00:20:55.045 --> 00:20:57.088
And what he did
with all the fight stuff...

370
00:20:57.255 --> 00:20:58.673
- Incredible.
-...it's amazing.

371
00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:02.385
It was his first, really, job
as a supervisor...

372
00:21:02.552 --> 00:21:04.721
...and he did, like, something
which is...

373
00:21:04.888 --> 00:21:08.350
...beyond everything we can have
with an old guy.

374
00:21:08.516 --> 00:21:10.935
Most of the time,
we didn't have a lot of time...

375
00:21:11.102 --> 00:21:14.189
...so it's always working, like,
almost with one take.

376
00:21:14.356 --> 00:21:15.857
Yeah, he really nailed it.

377
00:21:16.024 --> 00:21:18.777
On this scene, by example,
he didn't have a lot of choice.

378
00:21:18.943 --> 00:21:22.113
- We got just one car, so....
- Exactly, you've got one shot at it.

379
00:21:22.322 --> 00:21:27.702
Yeah, we came from-- And we bring,
like, two SUVs from France, that's it.

380
00:21:28.578 --> 00:21:32.040
And the two SUVs were, like,
not working so well either.

381
00:21:32.207 --> 00:21:35.710
A lot of disasters with that one.
The gas tank was on the wrong side.

382
00:21:35.877 --> 00:21:38.421
Yeah, more and more,
you forget your past...

383
00:21:38.588 --> 00:21:41.966
-...like the song in the opening title.
- Exactly.

384
00:21:42.133 --> 00:21:46.012
You just keep the good memories and
forget that everything was not so easy.

385
00:21:46.221 --> 00:21:48.431
- Everything was a challenge.
- Yeah, everything.

386
00:21:48.598 --> 00:21:52.644
Everything become more difficult in the
desert because of the wind, the sand.

387
00:21:52.811 --> 00:21:56.481
I mean, for all the equipment,
camera and stuff, light...

388
00:21:56.689 --> 00:21:58.191
...it's very, very hard.

389
00:21:58.358 --> 00:22:01.694
It's incredible how the actors
just were so good with all the weather.

390
00:22:01.861 --> 00:22:04.656
- We never had any problems.
- I have a theory that--

391
00:22:04.823 --> 00:22:08.243
I think the fact
that they were so in hard condition...

392
00:22:08.827 --> 00:22:13.748
...that really helped them to find all
the good behavior for their characters...

393
00:22:13.915 --> 00:22:18.628
...because they were in
the same exact condition...

394
00:22:18.795 --> 00:22:20.880
-...as the character in the story.
- Exactly.

395
00:22:21.047 --> 00:22:23.716
They were, like, stuck
in the middle of the desert...

396
00:22:23.925 --> 00:22:27.679
...with, like, you know, like,
little bit of water and heat.

397
00:22:27.887 --> 00:22:31.099
And so they were, like,
just living as they are.

398
00:22:31.266 --> 00:22:33.143
Yeah, it was perfect.

399
00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:37.939
They all had a great time. All the actors
talk about what a great time they had.

400
00:22:38.106 --> 00:22:41.025
Yeah, and that was-- You know,
because it was very intense...

401
00:22:41.192 --> 00:22:45.238
...and we were all living together in
the same hotel in the same place...

402
00:22:45.405 --> 00:22:46.948
...and with the crew members--

403
00:22:47.115 --> 00:22:49.117
Because it was not only
an American crew...

404
00:22:49.284 --> 00:22:51.786
...it was people coming
from all around the world...

405
00:22:51.953 --> 00:22:54.914
...from South Africa, from Romania,
from Italy, from France...

406
00:22:55.081 --> 00:22:56.666
...from Thailand, from England...

407
00:22:56.833 --> 00:22:59.461
-...from Australia.
- I think we had 18 different nationalities.

408
00:22:59.627 --> 00:23:03.298
Yeah, it was just amazing.
And everyone, like, really bonded.

409
00:23:03.506 --> 00:23:04.841
Yeah, really bonded.

410
00:23:05.008 --> 00:23:07.552
- It was amazing.
- We actually had a great time.

411
00:23:07.969 --> 00:23:11.306
There was another movie
staying at the hotel.

412
00:23:11.473 --> 00:23:14.142
Another shoot was at the hotel,
for <i>The Ten Commandments</i>.

413
00:23:14.309 --> 00:23:16.436
- And then the Brad Pitt movie earlier.
- Yeah.

414
00:23:16.603 --> 00:23:18.563
It was fun,
like a small little world.

415
00:23:18.730 --> 00:23:22.233
The only thing which was....
Everything was quite hard...

416
00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:25.612
-...but the dogs were like a nightmare.
- The dogs were a challenge.

417
00:23:25.778 --> 00:23:28.406
The dogs were a nightmare
because, of course...

418
00:23:28.573 --> 00:23:31.618
...you can't make the dog work all day.
They have to work very--

419
00:23:31.784 --> 00:23:35.288
Like, a short time because it's so hot
that it's very hard for them.

420
00:23:35.497 --> 00:23:39.375
So even with the heat,
to have trained dogs, it's very hard...

421
00:23:39.542 --> 00:23:42.921
...because, you know,
they just care about, you know, heat.

422
00:23:43.713 --> 00:23:46.382
Yeah, you can still ask to an actor
to make some effort.

423
00:23:46.549 --> 00:23:49.594
The dog, it's impossible. After
two takes, he doesn't want to do it.

424
00:23:49.761 --> 00:23:50.803
[COMMENTATOR CHUCKLING]

425
00:23:50.970 --> 00:23:54.307
That song, "California Dreamin',"
was a long one.

426
00:23:54.474 --> 00:23:57.810
Was a big, big fight
also to get that.

427
00:23:57.977 --> 00:24:01.898
Because we wanted a song that
everyone in the family can listen to...

428
00:24:02.065 --> 00:24:04.609
...and just make the scene like
everything is fine.

429
00:24:04.776 --> 00:24:08.446
You know, it's only an accident, you are
stuck in the middle of the desert...

430
00:24:08.613 --> 00:24:12.200
...but you're still in U.S. It's not
a problem, they're used to do that.

431
00:24:12.367 --> 00:24:16.913
They can spend the night here,
they have water, they have food.

432
00:24:17.080 --> 00:24:21.668
So everything is fine, you know. It's not
like, "Okay, we are starting to panic.

433
00:24:21.834 --> 00:24:25.046
And we are trying
to count the bullets we have...

434
00:24:25.213 --> 00:24:26.923
...and we're going to--" You know.

435
00:24:28.258 --> 00:24:30.718
Right now, it's okay.
Everything's fine.

436
00:24:30.885 --> 00:24:33.555
Even if you know that
it wasn't an accident.

437
00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.474
BOB: it makes you feel kind of powerful.
You might like it.

438
00:24:36.641 --> 00:24:39.519
I don't think so.
I'd probably just shoot my foot off.

439
00:24:39.727 --> 00:24:41.312
You know, he's right.

440
00:24:41.854 --> 00:24:44.148
He'd probably shoot his foot off.

441
00:24:46.192 --> 00:24:48.945
COMMENTARY:
That scene, where he's looking at...

442
00:24:49.112 --> 00:24:50.154
Brenda.

443
00:24:50.321 --> 00:24:55.368
Yes, Brenda, and his wife is
watching him looking at her...

444
00:24:55.535 --> 00:24:58.580
...was like--
We were really, like, asking...

