00:36:38.779 --> 00:36:41.699
- And I remember the--
- And here you can see...

668
00:36:41.865 --> 00:36:45.411
...the fishing pole in the boat.
The one that he's going to pick up...

669
00:36:45.577 --> 00:36:47.538
...and bring back to his family.

670
00:36:47.705 --> 00:36:49.581
One of the first meetings
that we got...

671
00:36:49.748 --> 00:36:52.126
...with Marianne Maddalena
and Wes Craven...

672
00:36:52.293 --> 00:36:55.379
...was to talk about ideas
for this remake.

673
00:36:55.546 --> 00:36:57.548
And the crater was one of the ideas.

674
00:36:57.715 --> 00:37:01.218
I mean, as soon as we found the idea
of the nuclear-testing background...

675
00:37:01.385 --> 00:37:03.929
...everything came very easy,
like the test village...

676
00:37:04.096 --> 00:37:08.684
...the look of the people from the hills
and the crater and everything.

677
00:37:09.351 --> 00:37:12.813
And I remember I had the idea
of bringing the crow and the raven--

678
00:37:12.980 --> 00:37:16.775
Like, it was during prep.
It wasn't before in the script...

679
00:37:16.942 --> 00:37:22.865
...to bring, like, the crow as
another element of something....

680
00:37:23.032 --> 00:37:24.366
- Ominous.
- Yeah, ominous.

681
00:37:24.533 --> 00:37:27.202
- Something is going wrong here.
- Deadly, yeah.

682
00:37:28.370 --> 00:37:31.165
That shot was, for CGI,
the most hard one to do.

683
00:37:31.332 --> 00:37:33.834
I don't know why, you know.
There is always one shot.

684
00:37:34.001 --> 00:37:37.171
And I think we tried
like 15 different times.

685
00:37:37.338 --> 00:37:40.049
At the end it's good.
It's not, like, really perfect...

686
00:37:40.215 --> 00:37:43.344
...but it's working very well.
The idea where we enter...

687
00:37:43.761 --> 00:37:46.513
...and then making the transition
to the night.

688
00:37:48.766 --> 00:37:53.270
That's-- That's a shot that we did
on the roof of the hotel during prep.

689
00:37:53.437 --> 00:37:57.024
That's exactly--
The moon shot was made...

690
00:37:57.191 --> 00:37:59.860
...during prep before everything.
That's the first shot.

691
00:38:00.027 --> 00:38:02.363
We were, like, at the pool
and we saw the moon...

692
00:38:02.529 --> 00:38:05.157
...and we said, "Yeah, we have
to pick up the camera...

693
00:38:05.324 --> 00:38:08.494
...and come back and go on the roof
and shot that." And we did it.

694
00:38:08.660 --> 00:38:10.996
It was two days
before we started the main shoot.

695
00:38:11.163 --> 00:38:13.082
I remember you guys
going up with Maxime.

696
00:38:13.248 --> 00:38:15.542
- It was even before, like a week.
- Yeah, a week.

697
00:38:15.709 --> 00:38:17.711
Just when we received
the camera, in fact.

698
00:38:17.878 --> 00:38:18.921
- Yeah, yeah.
- Exactly.

699
00:38:19.088 --> 00:38:20.756
The camera just arrived and we...

700
00:38:20.923 --> 00:38:24.385
- You ran out and got--
- Like a toy. Like the day after Christmas.

701
00:38:24.551 --> 00:38:27.638
-"Let's go."
- Yeah, "Let's play."

702
00:38:30.474 --> 00:38:32.434
David Franco,
the music supervisor...

703
00:38:32.601 --> 00:38:36.271
...found that song,
"In the Valley of the Sun"...

704
00:38:36.438 --> 00:38:38.857
...which is amazing,
that we use at the end.

705
00:38:39.024 --> 00:38:42.277
Because of Mark,
our editor assistant...

706
00:38:42.486 --> 00:38:44.988
...put that in the editing
and it was great.

707
00:38:45.155 --> 00:38:47.491
It brings something.
It's like "More and More."

708
00:38:47.658 --> 00:38:52.204
It's like a reminder of that country music
that just, you know...

709
00:38:52.371 --> 00:38:54.998
Talk about, like, another time,
another...

710
00:38:55.165 --> 00:38:57.626
- Things were more positive.
- Yeah.

711
00:38:57.793 --> 00:39:00.087
- But almost too positive.
- Too positive.

712
00:39:00.254 --> 00:39:01.855
- Too good to be true.
- Yeah, exactly.

713
00:39:01.922 --> 00:39:04.508
BOB: I got some water, all right?

714
00:39:13.475 --> 00:39:15.978
COMMENTARY: And everything here,
all that scene, was shot...

715
00:39:16.145 --> 00:39:18.230
...the two last days of the shooting
by night.

716
00:39:18.397 --> 00:39:21.233
So we already did that.

717
00:39:21.400 --> 00:39:23.527
And here we were, like,
in the middle of the night.

718
00:39:23.694 --> 00:39:26.572
At the end of the night,
and the sun was coming.

719
00:39:26.738 --> 00:39:30.659
And it was just, like, half an hour,
one hour to do it.

720
00:39:30.826 --> 00:39:33.245
So the only solution...

721
00:39:33.412 --> 00:39:38.792
...was to separate. So I was, like--
I'm operating the camera here.

722
00:39:38.959 --> 00:39:43.547
And in the other room,
Maxime is doing the other camera.

723
00:39:43.714 --> 00:39:45.215
And we are shooting
in the same time.

724
00:39:45.382 --> 00:39:48.427
It's only, like, one-take shots.

725
00:39:48.594 --> 00:39:53.390
So, in fact, we are following him
from one room to the other room.

726
00:39:54.016 --> 00:39:55.434
And it's funny.

727
00:39:55.601 --> 00:39:58.228
It was the only way,
because you already can see...

728
00:39:58.520 --> 00:40:01.315
...the daylight coming outside
by the window.

729
00:40:01.482 --> 00:40:03.442
Those were the last shots
of the movie.

730
00:40:04.026 --> 00:40:07.738
- In Ouarzazate, yeah.
- In Ouarzazate, exactly.

731
00:40:14.161 --> 00:40:18.582
What I like is, like, Maxime Alexandre,
our DP, did something...

732
00:40:18.749 --> 00:40:22.211
...which is he developed really what he
did on <i>High Tension</i>, our previous movie.

733
00:40:22.377 --> 00:40:28.509
He really built around the contrast
between warm and cold light.

734
00:40:28.675 --> 00:40:32.221
In every shot by night,
you can really feel the very heat...

735
00:40:32.387 --> 00:40:35.557
...of, like, yellow, orange, red light.

736
00:40:35.724 --> 00:40:41.855
And in the other hand, you have, like,
the blue, cyan, green light of the night.

737
00:40:42.022 --> 00:40:44.775
And everything is always
in the opposition...

738
00:40:44.942 --> 00:40:46.735
...and backlit. It's never flat.

739
00:40:46.902 --> 00:40:48.445
He really works with the contrast.

740
00:40:48.612 --> 00:40:52.407
And I think that's what makes
an horror movie a good horror movie.

741
00:40:52.574 --> 00:40:54.493
It's when you really
play with the contrast.

742
00:40:54.660 --> 00:40:58.247
Contrasts in silence and sound,
contrasts in between emotions.

743
00:40:58.413 --> 00:41:01.208
Contrast between light, of course.

744
00:41:01.375 --> 00:41:05.128
And everything.
Everything is about the contrast.

745
00:41:06.255 --> 00:41:08.131
There's Alix Taylor in that photograph.

746
00:41:08.298 --> 00:41:12.511
- Yeah, Alix Taylor, exactly.
- Who's our exec in charge of production.

747
00:41:12.678 --> 00:41:14.513
She volunteered
to be the mutants' mother...

748
00:41:14.680 --> 00:41:17.015
...and then volunteered her daughter
to be a baby mutant.

749
00:41:17.182 --> 00:41:18.976
Exactly.

750
00:41:28.443 --> 00:41:29.778
BOB:
Yeah.

751
00:41:32.864 --> 00:41:33.991
[ENGINE STALLS]

752
00:41:35.409 --> 00:41:37.369
ATTENDANT:
Jupiter.

753
00:41:39.788 --> 00:41:43.667
I got a buckshot, you hear?

754
00:41:43.959 --> 00:41:45.794
Hey, mister.

755
00:41:49.214 --> 00:41:52.217
COMMENTARY: This was a controversial
scene with the MPAA, wasn't it?

756
00:41:52.926 --> 00:41:54.761
- That scene, yeah.
- The scene coming up?

757
00:41:54.928 --> 00:41:57.931
- Didn't we get a lot--?
- Yeah, yeah, the committing suicide.

758
00:41:58.098 --> 00:41:59.474
The MPAA was...

759
00:41:59.641 --> 00:42:01.852
As the audience were, like,
very shocked...

760
00:42:02.019 --> 00:42:04.104
...of the way we show--

761
00:42:04.271 --> 00:42:06.315
The gas-station attendant
blowing his head off.

762
00:42:06.481 --> 00:42:10.402
Exactly. It was so real.
And we are very proud of that effect.

763
00:42:10.569 --> 00:42:13.947
Because, in fact, it's not so simple.

764
00:42:14.114 --> 00:42:16.450
On one hand, you have the actors
playing the scene...

765
00:42:16.617 --> 00:42:18.160
...and putting the gun under his chin.

766
00:42:18.327 --> 00:42:22.164
And then you have a puppet
of the actors very close.

767
00:42:22.331 --> 00:42:24.333
And you have to lock the position
of the camera...

768
00:42:24.499 --> 00:42:26.543
...and then you do
just a simple morphing...

769
00:42:27.127 --> 00:42:30.797
...between the real actor
and the dummy.

770
00:42:30.964 --> 00:42:32.299
And the result is fantastic.

771
00:42:32.466 --> 00:42:35.177
You really have the feeling
that he's, like, shooting himself.

772
00:42:35.344 --> 00:42:37.846
JUPITER:
Daddy.

773
00:42:38.472 --> 00:42:40.891
COMMENTARY: I love that shot.
You really have the feeling...

774
00:42:41.058 --> 00:42:42.976
...that he is, like, shooting
to the audience.

775
00:42:43.143 --> 00:42:44.811
Shooting towards the audience.

776
00:42:44.978 --> 00:42:46.313
And all the voices, of course...

777
00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:48.815
...like, all the actors,
were not here when we did that.

778
00:42:48.982 --> 00:42:51.526
And so it was, like,
PA doing the voices.

779
00:42:51.693 --> 00:42:53.695
That was very funny.

780
00:42:54.071 --> 00:42:55.906
That was very funny.

781
00:42:56.365 --> 00:42:57.866
JUPITER:
Daddy.

782
00:42:59.284 --> 00:43:02.829
COMMENTARY: This is a really scary
scene because Big Bob is so scared.

783
00:43:03.288 --> 00:43:06.708
Yeah, and he is the guy
who's not supposed to be scared.

784
00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.086
And that shot of Jupiter
in the rear-view mirror...

785
00:43:09.252 --> 00:43:11.963
...was made by second unit,
like, two weeks before.

786
00:43:12.130 --> 00:43:14.174
- Without the car.
- Without the car.

787
00:43:14.341 --> 00:43:17.010
Just, like, two pieces of glass
in the back and the front...

788
00:43:17.177 --> 00:43:19.680
-...and the rear mirror. That's it.
- Yeah, and all the dummy--

789
00:43:19.846 --> 00:43:22.265
Because we did the scene
with Ted Levine...

790
00:43:22.432 --> 00:43:23.975
...being smashed against the window.

791
00:43:24.142 --> 00:43:29.856
But also with, like, a very good dummy
by K.N.B. against the windshield.

792
00:43:30.023 --> 00:43:33.485
And that second unit did that
the next day or the following day.

793
00:43:33.652 --> 00:43:36.822
- Yeah, the following day.
- The following day, yeah, on-stage.

794
00:43:36.988 --> 00:43:38.323
That's also second unit.

795
00:43:38.490 --> 00:43:42.160
On-stage, Joseph Nemec
built, like, a part of the mine.

796
00:43:48.542 --> 00:43:51.336
And the lamp, the gas lamp
that they're using...

797
00:43:51.503 --> 00:43:53.547
...I found that in a souk...

798
00:43:53.714 --> 00:43:57.968
...in a market over there in Morocco.
It's a really miner sodium lamp.

799
00:43:58.135 --> 00:44:01.972
- Amazing. Did you keep it?
- No, the guy refused to sell it.

800
00:44:02.139 --> 00:44:04.850
- Oh, so you just borrowed it?
- Yeah, yeah. Just for the scene.

801
00:44:05.475 --> 00:44:08.311
BRENDA: Wait, I'm here!
I'll be back in a minute!

802
00:44:11.857 --> 00:44:13.817
COMMENTARY:
Everyone thought that I was crazy...

803
00:44:13.984 --> 00:44:15.902
...to think about that shot here...

804
00:44:16.069 --> 00:44:18.280
...because it was very hard to access.

805
00:44:18.447 --> 00:44:20.991
And I wanted to have a crane shot
starting on the landscape...

806
00:44:21.158 --> 00:44:24.494
...and then craning down in the canyon
where they were.

807
00:44:24.661 --> 00:44:27.289
And that was not only
impossible to do...

808
00:44:27.456 --> 00:44:30.792
...it was impossible
just to reach the place with the crane.

809
00:44:30.959 --> 00:44:34.713
So for one whole day,
grips were, like...

810
00:44:34.880 --> 00:44:39.426
...bringing the crane on their shoulder
to the place...

811
00:44:39.593 --> 00:44:42.596
...just to make that shot possible.

812
00:44:42.763 --> 00:44:44.681
- But it works very well.
- Yeah, it's great.

813
00:44:44.848 --> 00:44:46.600
You get this feeling of vertigo.

814
00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:57.778
ETHEL: Okay, let me just--
Oh, honey, the hair.

815
00:44:58.111 --> 00:44:59.237
BOBBY:
Just....

816
00:44:59.404 --> 00:45:02.532
You know, you really are so lucky
that Brenda found you.

817
00:45:02.699 --> 00:45:06.870
I mean, what if you'd had to spend
the whole night out there in the cold?

818
00:45:07.204 --> 00:45:09.164
COMMENTARY:
Here you can feel that the trailer--

819
00:45:09.331 --> 00:45:11.416
Even if you put, like, everyone
in the same frame...

820
00:45:11.583 --> 00:45:13.835
...just to make the trailer
a little bit more small...

821
00:45:14.002 --> 00:45:18.006
...but you can see that the trailer
is very big. You can really feel that.

822
00:45:19.382 --> 00:45:21.802
LYNN: But we heard something.

823
00:45:21.968 --> 00:45:23.678
Some sort of breathing.

824
00:45:23.845 --> 00:45:25.680
What breathing?

825
00:45:27.307 --> 00:45:28.850
COMMENTARY:
This scene was shot also...

826
00:45:29.017 --> 00:45:31.728
...but we decide to cut it
during the editing room.

827
00:45:31.895 --> 00:45:34.039
- Yeah, yeah.
- The scene where she's talking about--

828
00:45:34.105 --> 00:45:37.192
They are talking about the CB
and what they heard on the CB.

829
00:45:37.359 --> 00:45:39.402
And we cut the scene
because, I mean...

830
00:45:39.569 --> 00:45:42.155
...we are talking about what's happened,
and we don't need that.

831
00:45:42.322 --> 00:45:46.368
We were with Bobby
and with Big Bob, so...

832
00:45:46.535 --> 00:45:51.456
So, you know, it was not very
helpful to understand.

833
00:45:51.623 --> 00:45:54.000
I think we get exactly
what's going on.

834
00:45:56.795 --> 00:45:59.381
We also decided to apply
what we did on <i>High Tension</i> here...

835
00:45:59.548 --> 00:46:02.509
...which is according to the level
of fear of what we are filming...

836
00:46:02.676 --> 00:46:05.554
...you change the way
you are filming, you know.

837
00:46:05.720 --> 00:46:08.014
It's more hand-held
when you are really scared.

838
00:46:08.181 --> 00:46:12.561
And it's more, like, high aerial and steady
when it's, you know, just about...

839
00:46:12.727 --> 00:46:15.355
...like, confident, and when you
are with the bad guy...

840
00:46:15.522 --> 00:46:19.067
...or when it's just about, like,
tension and suspense.

841
00:46:24.155 --> 00:46:26.157
BOBBY:
Beast!

842
00:46:26.366 --> 00:46:27.534
- Beast!
DOUG: Hey, Bobby.

843
00:46:27.701 --> 00:46:29.661
- Jesus Christ!
- Hey, whoa!

844
00:46:30.036 --> 00:46:32.914
Stop pointing the gun at me. Please.

845
00:46:33.623 --> 00:46:36.585
- Jesus, Bobby.
- Doug, I'm sorry, man.

846
00:46:36.751 --> 00:46:38.587
It's me.

847
00:46:39.546 --> 00:46:41.840
COMMENTARY: I love the look of Doug
with his hat...

848
00:46:42.007 --> 00:46:43.675
...and his, like, you know, jacket.

849
00:46:43.842 --> 00:46:46.761
He looks so, like, not the hero.

850
00:46:46.928 --> 00:46:49.764
You really can't-- You know,
you can't bet on him.

851
00:46:49.931 --> 00:46:53.143
- Yeah.
- He won't-- He won't survive.

852
00:46:53.310 --> 00:46:55.937
He's going to die.
He's not going to be the hero.

853
00:46:56.104 --> 00:46:59.649
Also, I think it's--
What is great with Aaron Stanford...

854
00:46:59.816 --> 00:47:02.569
He's really, like-- You know,
people during the test screening...

855
00:47:02.736 --> 00:47:06.615
...were, like, giving who is
their favorite character in the movie.

856
00:47:06.781 --> 00:47:08.783
And they were all saying,
"Doug at the end."

857
00:47:08.950 --> 00:47:11.578
And the least favorite was
"Doug at the beginning."

858
00:47:11.745 --> 00:47:13.079
- Exactly.
- That was great.

859
00:47:13.246 --> 00:47:15.498
- That show that the arc is here.
- They loved it--

860
00:47:15.665 --> 00:47:17.834
What they said is they loved it
when Doug "manned up."

861
00:47:18.001 --> 00:47:19.336
- Remember?
- Yeah.

862
00:47:19.502 --> 00:47:22.088
That's really about--
We were looking, like...

863
00:47:22.255 --> 00:47:25.258
...the new Dustin Hoffman
in <i>Straw Dogs</i> for that movie.

864
00:47:25.425 --> 00:47:27.844
And Aaron Stanford is just perfect.

865
00:47:28.011 --> 00:47:30.221
Yeah, he was great.
He understand very quickly.

866
00:47:30.388 --> 00:47:35.226
And he was very open to do this
coward character at the beginning.

867
00:47:35.393 --> 00:47:37.228
To play the antihero.

868
00:47:37.395 --> 00:47:40.607
And to go very deep in that process.
So that was great.

869
00:47:40.774 --> 00:47:43.026
Here you can really see also the....

870
00:47:43.193 --> 00:47:45.070
You know, Maxime, an excellent job.

871
00:47:45.236 --> 00:47:49.866
Because in one hand, you have
really, like, the heat of the campfire...

872
00:47:50.033 --> 00:47:51.868
...and in the other hand
you have the night...

873
00:47:52.035 --> 00:47:56.790
...and the opposition between
heat and cold light.

874
00:47:56.957 --> 00:48:00.460
That's a day-for-night.
That's the only one we did.

875
00:48:00.710 --> 00:48:05.966
It was at the end of the day
of the labyrinth scene with Bobby.

876
00:48:06.132 --> 00:48:08.510
We did that with the dog.
It was just one take.

877
00:48:08.677 --> 00:48:11.930
And did it perfectly
for the first time in the shooting.

878
00:48:12.597 --> 00:48:15.517
DOUG: No, Bobby, I'm exhausted.
I need to get some sleep.

879
00:48:15.684 --> 00:48:18.436
No, no, no. It's fine.
You'll be more comfortable here.

880
00:48:18.603 --> 00:48:20.480
Because I'll sleep on the floor.

881
00:48:20.647 --> 00:48:23.316
Mom and Brenda will be up front,
you and Lynn in back.

882
00:48:23.483 --> 00:48:25.568
We got extra sleeping bags
and stuff too.

883
00:48:25.735 --> 00:48:30.031
Bobby, you got six people sleeping in a
three-person trailer. It's not comfortable.

884
00:48:30.198 --> 00:48:32.659
It's a little bit weird. Okay?

885
00:48:32.826 --> 00:48:34.411
Honey, you gonna bring the water?

886
00:48:34.577 --> 00:48:37.247
COMMENTARY: We also did a lot
of rehearsal before the shooting...

887
00:48:37.414 --> 00:48:41.084
...with all the actors,
just to be sure of the blocking.

888
00:48:41.418 --> 00:48:44.713
DOUG: Baby, you coming?
LYNN: I'm almost ready.

889
00:48:45.296 --> 00:48:47.215
What's going on?

890
00:48:48.883 --> 00:48:52.637
COMMENTARY: And Bobby's character
was one of the....

891
00:48:53.847 --> 00:48:56.182
Hard character to find.

892
00:48:56.349 --> 00:48:58.560
I mean, Dan Byrd came in the room
and really showed...

893
00:48:58.727 --> 00:49:00.353
...that he was really the character.

894
00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:02.272
But with all the Bobby
that we saw before...

895
00:49:02.439 --> 00:49:04.649
-...it wasn't so....
- So easy.

896
00:49:04.816 --> 00:49:07.819
He has to be young, but in
the same time he needs to be, like...

897
00:49:07.986 --> 00:49:12.574
Big strength inside him.
Even if he can cry...

898
00:49:12.741 --> 00:49:16.536
...even if he can be very, you know,
emotive and sensitive...

899
00:49:16.703 --> 00:49:20.331
...he needs to be the one
that gets out for revenge first.

900
00:49:20.498 --> 00:49:26.713
He is the one that's going to
motivate Doug to become the hero.

901
00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:28.965
And he has also to express
his feelings...

902
00:49:29.132 --> 00:49:33.178
...that he knows that something
is going wrong here.

903
00:49:33.511 --> 00:49:38.058
And he can't tell to the people,
and he really managed to express that.

904
00:49:38.224 --> 00:49:40.602
Oh, Emilie. We haven't really
talked at all about Emilie.

905
00:49:40.769 --> 00:49:42.203
- Yeah, Emilie--
- She was amazing.

906
00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:46.066
She was amazing. And, you know,
we met a lot of young actresses...

907
00:49:46.232 --> 00:49:48.026
...but she came very early...

908
00:49:48.193 --> 00:49:51.696
...and she became, like,
the only possibility.

909
00:49:51.863 --> 00:49:53.114
She came in the room...

910
00:49:53.281 --> 00:49:55.325
...and played back to back
three different scenes...

911
00:49:55.492 --> 00:49:57.535
...without even, like,
a pause or break.

912
00:49:57.702 --> 00:50:01.623
And it was, like, you know,
normal life, screaming and crying.

913
00:50:01.790 --> 00:50:04.459
And back to back,
it was just super real...

914
00:50:04.626 --> 00:50:10.340
...to see her go in such extreme emotion
in so short of time.

915
00:50:11.049 --> 00:50:15.887
She's one of the best young actresses.

916
00:50:16.054 --> 00:50:19.224
Even, maybe, the best.
I mean, she's amazing.

917
00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:24.813
And we put her through it.
She really got bloody, got out up....

918
00:50:24.979 --> 00:50:27.148
Yeah, she got cut up.
She got, like, a-- Well, yeah--

919
00:50:27.315 --> 00:50:29.359
She went through the story for real.

920
00:50:29.526 --> 00:50:31.653
- She was seriously-- Yeah.
- For real.

921
00:50:31.820 --> 00:50:37.659
Because some of the hills dweller
are, like, really violent in life.

922
00:50:42.622 --> 00:50:45.208
I think she had about 200 little cuts
at one point on her arm...

923
00:50:45.375 --> 00:50:47.252
-...from the candy glass.
- Yeah, maybe not 200.

924
00:50:47.418 --> 00:50:49.420
No, little teeny-tiny--
She was a trouper, though.

925
00:50:49.587 --> 00:50:50.922
Yeah.

926
00:50:51.089 --> 00:50:53.716
I remember here
we put some silhouettes...

927
00:50:53.883 --> 00:50:58.513
...of Doug and Lynn inside the SUV.

928
00:50:58.680 --> 00:51:00.348
But you can't see them at all.

929
00:51:00.515 --> 00:51:03.143
Like, pretending to make love
or something like that.

930
00:51:03.309 --> 00:51:06.855
They are here. They're, like, you know,
the PA, pretending to make love.

931
00:51:07.021 --> 00:51:09.649
Who was that?
That was Olivier and Miriam.

932
00:51:09.816 --> 00:51:12.944
- Exactly.
- Exactly. Olivier got all the good jobs.

933
00:51:13.111 --> 00:51:15.446
Our second assistant director.

934
00:51:15.613 --> 00:51:18.074
He held the umbrella
over Brenda as well...

935
00:51:18.241 --> 00:51:20.076
-...when she was in her bra top.
- Yeah.

936
00:51:20.243 --> 00:51:22.370
- Exactly.
- He had the hard jobs.

937
00:51:26.249 --> 00:51:29.043
This shot is funny.
It remembers, like, <i>High Tension</i>.

938
00:51:29.210 --> 00:51:32.422
Yeah, it's really like a tribute
to <i>High Tension</i>. Same shot.

939
00:51:32.589 --> 00:51:35.425
With the hand coming in the frame,
with the same:

940
00:51:38.011 --> 00:51:40.221
"Whoosh." Like, "boom."

941
00:51:40.388 --> 00:51:42.265
Exactly the same.

942
00:51:44.559 --> 00:51:46.060
It was a hard decision to take.

943
00:51:46.227 --> 00:51:48.605
When we're going to show,
for the first time...

944
00:51:48.771 --> 00:51:51.232
...the face of Pluto.
Are we waiting her to wake up?

945
00:51:51.399 --> 00:51:53.484
Or are we, like, showing him, like...

946
00:51:53.651 --> 00:51:57.739
...enjoying the vision of her, like,
naked body, under the sheets?

947
00:51:58.406 --> 00:52:00.617
In the original movie,
we can see Pluto, you know...

948
00:52:00.783 --> 00:52:05.205
-...taking out the gas from the car.
- Siphoning the gas.

949
00:52:05.371 --> 00:52:08.499
- And we shot that.
- We shot that...

950
00:52:08.666 --> 00:52:12.003
...but we decided to cut it off because
it was more scary...

951
00:52:12.170 --> 00:52:14.589
...to have Pluto's face here...

952
00:52:14.756 --> 00:52:16.758
-...for the first time.
- For the first time, yeah.

953
00:52:18.426 --> 00:52:20.136
[GROWLING]

954
00:52:20.345 --> 00:52:22.347
[LAUGHING]

955
00:52:23.181 --> 00:52:25.600
COMMENTARY: And that's also
one of the reasons I remember...

956
00:52:25.767 --> 00:52:28.144
...we were talking
with the line producer about.

957
00:52:28.311 --> 00:52:31.898
Like, why we wanted to shoot the movie
outside by night...

958
00:52:32.065 --> 00:52:33.608
...for real and not on-stage.

959
00:52:33.775 --> 00:52:38.696
It's because, even by night,
we refuse to not see....

960
00:52:38.863 --> 00:52:41.699
To not only see the trailer,
but see also the landscape.

961
00:52:41.866 --> 00:52:44.118
It was very important
to keep the landscape...

962
00:52:44.285 --> 00:52:47.538
...part of the location all the time.

963
00:52:48.665 --> 00:52:51.668
So everything was made
on location by night.

964
00:52:51.834 --> 00:52:54.337
Which is not the case
in the usual films.

965
00:52:54.504 --> 00:52:57.257
You know, it's not very easy
to go into the desert by night...

966
00:52:57.423 --> 00:53:01.261
...with, like, 100 people and shoot.

967
00:53:01.928 --> 00:53:06.474
And once again, scorpions and snakes
are, like, everywhere.

968
00:53:06.641 --> 00:53:10.228
And nighttime is when
they really live their life.

969
00:53:10.395 --> 00:53:13.273
So we told everyone that,
you know:

970
00:53:13.439 --> 00:53:14.941
"If you have to give a phone call...

971
00:53:15.108 --> 00:53:18.111
...or if you have to rest,
or I don't know what...

972
00:53:18.278 --> 00:53:20.613
...don't go out of the light,
because...."

973
00:53:20.780 --> 00:53:23.866
"Don't sit on a rock."  There were
rocks everywhere and it was really dark.

974
00:53:24.033 --> 00:53:26.202
- It's amazing no one fell over.
- Yeah.

975
00:53:26.369 --> 00:53:29.080
- It was definitely....
- It was cool to shoot during night.

976
00:53:29.247 --> 00:53:31.457
That was the only moment
we can breathe a little bit.

977
00:53:31.624 --> 00:53:34.002
- And to have the temperature go down.
- Exactly.

978
00:53:34.168 --> 00:53:37.547
And it was so beautiful,
all the stars in the sky.

979
00:53:37.714 --> 00:53:41.175
I mean, I'm going to have
my romantic moment.

980
00:53:41.342 --> 00:53:43.094
- It was really amazing.
- It was gorgeous.

981
00:53:43.261 --> 00:53:47.849
So that shot is made on production.
It's a Steadicam shot...

982
00:53:48.016 --> 00:53:51.436
...that we then apply
a variation speed on it.

983
00:53:51.602 --> 00:53:56.482
And Ted Levine was really on the tree,
like, yelling and screaming.

984
00:53:56.649 --> 00:53:59.944
And we add then the flames
and the fire.

985
00:54:00.111 --> 00:54:01.821
But because of the variation speed...

986
00:54:01.988 --> 00:54:06.367
...we had to have him play slow motion.
Like, six-time slow motion.

987
00:54:06.534 --> 00:54:07.869
And he did it perfectly.

988
00:54:08.036 --> 00:54:10.997
You have to imagine also
the Steadicam operator...

989
00:54:11.164 --> 00:54:13.333
...who walked during, like, two minutes
to reach him.

990
00:54:13.499 --> 00:54:16.544
Yeah, it's-- The whole shot in real time,
it's, like, two minutes' walk.

991
00:54:16.711 --> 00:54:18.046
Two minutes' and a half walk.

992
00:54:18.212 --> 00:54:21.549
Which is a big, big, big deal
for a Steadicamer.

993
00:54:24.969 --> 00:54:28.848
It's funny how that guy is, like,
enjoying by dressing him in a skirt.

994
00:54:29.932 --> 00:54:34.479
- It's the first time we see Lizard.
- And so-- Yeah, and Big Bob on fire...

995
00:54:34.645 --> 00:54:38.066
...was made from all the different
kind of processes you can have.

996
00:54:38.274 --> 00:54:41.569
In one hand, you have, like,
really Ted Levine on the tree...

997
00:54:41.736 --> 00:54:44.947
...like, pretending to burn.
And then you add, like, the CGI.

998
00:54:45.114 --> 00:54:48.117
You have, like, part of his body,
like here.

999
00:54:48.284 --> 00:54:50.620
That's really him with CGI.

1000
00:54:50.787 --> 00:54:53.915
- And then you have, like, a dummy.
- CG and makeup also.

1001
00:54:54.082 --> 00:54:57.585
CG and makeup, yeah,
because you see the skin bubbling.

1002
00:54:57.752 --> 00:55:00.046
- A moving dummy, articulated dummy.
- And a moving...

1003
00:55:00.213 --> 00:55:02.173
...articulated dummy
that we put fire on it.

1004
00:55:02.340 --> 00:55:04.050
- Yeah.
- So it was just one take.

1005
00:55:04.217 --> 00:55:07.887
Because after, like,
20 seconds of fire...

1006
00:55:08.054 --> 00:55:11.057
...the dummy stopped working.
Of course, because it's burning.

1007
00:55:11.224 --> 00:55:14.852
And two close-up shots of
Big Bob burning, the arm and the head.

1008
00:55:15.019 --> 00:55:18.398
That's one of the shot that the MPAA
asked us to cut because it was--

1009
00:55:18.564 --> 00:55:21.275
- It was pretty intense.
- Pretty intense, and....

1010
00:55:21.442 --> 00:55:24.904
So the bird, the same. The bird was,
like, of course, a fake bird.

1011
00:55:25.071 --> 00:55:26.155
Yes, of course it was.

1012
00:55:26.322 --> 00:55:28.491
Yeah, and the actor refused
to eat a real one.

1013
00:55:28.658 --> 00:55:30.076
[COMMENTATOR CHUCKLES]

1014
00:55:30.660 --> 00:55:32.578
And so it was, like, really one take...

1015
00:55:32.745 --> 00:55:36.374
...and, like, three cameras,
like, running everywhere.

1016
00:55:36.541 --> 00:55:37.917
And it was like, "Okay, guys.

1017
00:55:38.084 --> 00:55:41.796
Do exactly how you feel
the shot with different lenses."

1018
00:55:41.963 --> 00:55:44.132
And we have some great material.

1019
00:55:44.298 --> 00:55:47.051
Because it looks real, it looks
really like a guy burning...

1020
00:55:47.218 --> 00:55:50.346
...and with everyone,
like, freaking out around him.

1021
00:55:52.014 --> 00:55:54.559
LIZARD:
I told you to move, so move!

1022
00:55:54.725 --> 00:55:56.978
COMMENTARY: Michael Bailey Smith,
who's playing Pluto...

1023
00:55:57.145 --> 00:55:58.771
...is amazing because....

1024
00:55:59.313 --> 00:56:04.735
The job of Greg Nicotero and K.N.B.
is one of the best jobs they have made.

1025
00:56:04.902 --> 00:56:08.531
It's amazing how the makeup
looks real on them.

1026
00:56:08.698 --> 00:56:10.283
But the way he acts...

1027
00:56:10.450 --> 00:56:14.829
...and the way he brought, like, his own
interpretation of the character...

1028
00:56:14.996 --> 00:56:17.039
...to Pluto is amazing.

1029
00:56:17.206 --> 00:56:18.958
It's very strong.

1030
00:56:19.125 --> 00:56:21.794
It was a big challenge
because everyone remembers...

1031
00:56:21.961 --> 00:56:25.256
...Michael Berryman in the original film
in the part of Pluto.

1032
00:56:25.423 --> 00:56:31.429
So it was a big deal to make it, like,
you know, like, different...

1033
00:56:31.596 --> 00:56:34.765
...and in the same time as strong
as it was in the original film.

1034
00:56:35.641 --> 00:56:40.271
And Michael did, like, something that--
I mean, beyond all the expectation.

1035
00:56:41.063 --> 00:56:45.443
And he became really
our favorite hills mutant.

1036
00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:52.617
Yeah, that's my assistant's hand
out the window, like...

1037
00:56:53.117 --> 00:56:54.952
...touching the--
You know, the blinds.

1038
00:56:55.119 --> 00:56:57.705
That was shot like a week before.

1039
00:56:57.872 --> 00:57:00.583
- She's doing very well, the raping.
- Oh, my God.

1040
00:57:00.750 --> 00:57:02.835
- I mean, it's--
- She does. She does a great job.

1041
00:57:03.002 --> 00:57:05.922
Now, all this wardrobe was--
The big story about the wardrobe:

1042
00:57:06.088 --> 00:57:08.132
That all of the key mutant wardrobe
was lost...

1043
00:57:08.299 --> 00:57:10.760
...three days before
we were about to shoot.

1044
00:57:10.927 --> 00:57:13.763
The shipment from L.A.
never arrived...

1045
00:57:13.930 --> 00:57:16.766
...so we had to re-create everything
within three days.

1046
00:57:16.933 --> 00:57:18.267
- And we did.
- Yeah.

1047
00:57:18.434 --> 00:57:20.311
It was the worst day--
The second-worst day...

1048
00:57:20.478 --> 00:57:22.939
...of my producing career
when I realized that--

1049
00:57:23.105 --> 00:57:24.440
- It really was.
- Yeah, I mean--

1050
00:57:24.607 --> 00:57:26.317
I just couldn't believe it happened.

1051
00:57:26.484 --> 00:57:28.903
I couldn't believe I had to tell
Alex and Greg it happened.

1052
00:57:29.070 --> 00:57:31.239
Luckily someone told you
before I had to.

1053
00:57:31.405 --> 00:57:33.741
But we did it.
We got it together...

1054
00:57:33.908 --> 00:57:37.870
...with Danny Glicker in L.A. and
Anna Lombardi in Ouarzazate...

1055
00:57:38.037 --> 00:57:39.372
...and we re-created their--

1056
00:57:39.539 --> 00:57:41.499
And all of this is re-created
within three days.

1057
00:57:42.500 --> 00:57:44.085
- It's pretty amazing.
- Yeah.

1058
00:57:45.878 --> 00:57:48.381
LIZARD:
Oh, you fat.

1059
00:57:50.424 --> 00:57:52.301
COMMENTARY:
All the hills' costumes, in fact...

1060
00:57:52.468 --> 00:57:54.470
...because all the Carter family
arrived, in fact.

1061
00:57:54.637 --> 00:57:57.139
Yeah, it was all the Hills--
it was all the mutants.

1062
00:57:59.433 --> 00:58:03.271
Which had taken months to design,
build and age. Months.

1063
00:58:03.437 --> 00:58:06.482
- It's amazing what she did.
- Yeah, it was incredible.

1064
00:58:06.649 --> 00:58:09.652
That's another shot
that the MPAA asked us to change.

1065
00:58:09.819 --> 00:58:12.196
Change our focus on the baby
and the gun.

1066
00:58:12.697 --> 00:58:17.243
But what is funny is, like, if you look
at all the dailies of that scene...

1067
00:58:17.410 --> 00:58:20.955
...you know, you see that the baby
is really enjoying the gun.

1068
00:58:21.122 --> 00:58:22.790
You know, she just doesn't care.

1069
00:58:22.957 --> 00:58:25.001
Nothing--
Blood didn't bother that baby.

1070
00:58:25.167 --> 00:58:29.755
And what's funny is, like, you can't
do a fake Magnum, silver...

1071
00:58:29.922 --> 00:58:32.216
...because it's very hard
and it looks fake.

1072
00:58:32.383 --> 00:58:35.303
And so before each shot
you have the mother of the baby here...

1073
00:58:35.469 --> 00:58:37.888
- Checking the gun.
-...and you have to present the gun...

1074
00:58:38.055 --> 00:58:40.808
...and so she's opening the gun,
looking inside, there is no bullet:

1075
00:58:40.975 --> 00:58:43.519
"Okay, you can play
with my baby and the gun."

1076
00:58:43.686 --> 00:58:45.021
- It was crazy.
- Oh, my gosh.

1077
00:58:45.187 --> 00:58:49.358
Yeah, and it was very hard because
we did in first unit some of the shots...

1078
00:58:49.525 --> 00:58:52.361
...but second unit was mandated
to come back...

1079
00:58:52.528 --> 00:58:55.031
...and do some other shots
of the gun on the baby...

1080
00:58:55.197 --> 00:58:56.824
...and that's not so easy to do.

1081
00:58:56.991 --> 00:59:00.369
Because even if there is no bullet
and there is no risk...

1082
00:59:01.203 --> 00:59:03.664
...you still have the feeling
of, like, putting a baby--

1083
00:59:03.831 --> 00:59:05.750
Aiming a baby--
Aiming a gun on the baby.

1084
00:59:05.916 --> 00:59:07.768
- Something feels very wrong about it.
- Yeah.

1085
00:59:07.835 --> 00:59:10.963
At the same time, there was a lot
of shots of the baby, you know, enjoys--

1086
00:59:11.130 --> 00:59:14.759
- The gun, it becomes like a toy.
- So she's touching it, it's shiny.

1087
00:59:14.925 --> 00:59:16.927
So we have to wait
that the baby cries, you know.

1088
00:59:17.094 --> 00:59:18.804
And that's the worst moment...

1089
00:59:18.971 --> 00:59:23.851
...you know, when you film the baby's
crying, and it's really awful.

1090
00:59:24.018 --> 00:59:25.186
That's also a big stunt.

1091
00:59:25.353 --> 00:59:27.146
We wanted to have, like...

1092
00:59:27.313 --> 00:59:31.442
...a very grotesque, dramatic
scene for Ethel's death.

1093
00:59:31.609 --> 00:59:34.487
And so it's, once again,
Cedric Proust...

1094
00:59:34.654 --> 00:59:37.782
...who did an amazing job
with this stunt double.

1095
00:59:37.948 --> 00:59:42.328
And what is funny was when we were,
like, editing in Paris with Baxter...

1096
00:59:42.495 --> 00:59:46.123
...at the end, he said, "You know,
you are lucky to have so many actors...

1097
00:59:46.290 --> 00:59:47.583
...that agree on playing...

1098
00:59:47.750 --> 00:59:49.710
-...you know, all the stunt stuff."
- Exactly.

1099
00:59:53.964 --> 00:59:58.344
That's a scene that the MPAA
was also very hard to convince.

1100
00:59:58.511 --> 01:00:01.722
Because you are not used to see,
like, a gunshot on-screen...

1101
01:00:02.348 --> 01:00:05.393
...on the head of,
like, young actresses.

1102
01:00:05.559 --> 01:00:08.270
And that was very, very intense
and violent.

1103
01:00:08.437 --> 01:00:11.357
And all that scene was, like,
pretty problematic for the MPAA...

1104
01:00:11.524 --> 01:00:15.695
...and that's why they ask us to cut,
like, almost one minute...

1105
01:00:15.903 --> 01:00:17.029
[CLICKS EMPTY]

1106
01:00:17.238 --> 01:00:19.699
...that you can see here now.

1107
01:00:19.907 --> 01:00:22.451
LIZARD: I'll come back for you.
- Brenda!

1108
01:00:25.079 --> 01:00:26.956
Bitch stuck me like a pig!

1109
01:00:28.165 --> 01:00:30.710
COMMENTARY: That was so hard
for them because they were, like--

1110
01:00:30.876 --> 01:00:34.422
Pluto, Michael Bailey Smith, but also
for Robert Joy, who was playing Lizard.

1111
01:00:34.588 --> 01:00:39.468
They were running in the night on the
rocks with prosthetics on their face...

1112
01:00:39.635 --> 01:00:43.764
...so they were, like, not able
to see really much what's going on.

1113
01:00:43.931 --> 01:00:47.393
So nobody fell, nobody break a leg.

1114
01:00:47.560 --> 01:00:49.186
- We didn't lose anyone.
- Yeah.

1115
01:00:49.353 --> 01:00:52.273
- And that was not so easy.
- No.

1116
01:00:52.440 --> 01:00:54.525
Yeah.

1117
01:00:58.112 --> 01:01:02.742
That's also something, like,
which reminds a lot of <i>High Tension</i>...

1118
01:01:02.908 --> 01:01:05.578
...where you have exactly
the same kind of...

1119
01:01:05.745 --> 01:01:10.374
...you know, like, dead coming
back to life for a last breath.

1120
01:01:10.541 --> 01:01:11.792
[LYNN GASPS]

1121
01:01:11.959 --> 01:01:14.128
DOUG:
Oh, God! Don't move.

1122
01:01:14.295 --> 01:01:15.671
Don't move, honey. Don't move.

1123
01:01:15.838 --> 01:01:18.424
COMMENTARY: But it's much
more emotional, of course, here.

1124
01:01:18.591 --> 01:01:20.843
DOUG:
You're gonna be okay.

1125
01:01:21.010 --> 01:01:23.846
Sweetheart. Okay.

1126
01:01:24.680 --> 01:01:26.307
Honey?

1127
01:01:26.474 --> 01:01:29.727
COMMENTARY: And dealing with blood
is always, like...

1128
01:01:29.894 --> 01:01:32.021
Always very hard
because blood is sticky...

1129
01:01:32.188 --> 01:01:37.318
...blood is, you know, like, dry
and then stuck everything.

1130
01:01:37.485 --> 01:01:42.406
For actress, it's, like, very,
very hard. And under the heat--

1131
01:01:42.573 --> 01:01:45.451
Fake blood is made often with sugar...

1132
01:01:45.618 --> 01:01:48.829
...and so flies are, like, everywhere,
like, around you.

1133
01:01:48.996 --> 01:01:50.331
So we were, like...

1134
01:01:50.498 --> 01:01:52.917
...not only trying to find
the best color for the blood...

1135
01:01:53.083 --> 01:01:55.419
...which is always
also a big challenge...

1136
01:01:55.586 --> 01:01:58.422
...because if you took blood
which is too orange or too red...

1137
01:01:58.589 --> 01:02:01.634
...it looks like ketchup and fake
and you don't believe in it.

1138
01:02:01.801 --> 01:02:06.472
So you have to find exactly the perfect
color for night light and also for daylight.

1139
01:02:06.639 --> 01:02:08.474
But here it was also...

1140
01:02:08.641 --> 01:02:11.477
...find some fake blood
which is not based on sugar...

1141
01:02:11.644 --> 01:02:16.565
...so you don't have, like, too much
insects around you during the time.

1142
01:02:16.732 --> 01:02:18.484
It was just disgusting.
It was so sticky.

1143
01:02:18.651 --> 01:02:20.903
And they were covered in blood
for most of the movie.

1144
01:02:21.070 --> 01:02:23.239
Ezra Buzzington,
who's playing Goggle...

1145
01:02:23.405 --> 01:02:28.702
...came for one day of shooting,
and it was one day of only second unit.

1146
01:02:28.869 --> 01:02:34.750
And he did all his stuff in, like,
half a day and half a night.

1147
01:02:34.917 --> 01:02:38.546
And it was a nightmare, I mean,
you can tell, for second unit...

1148
01:02:38.712 --> 01:02:40.965
...because everything broke that night.

1149
01:02:41.131 --> 01:02:44.844
- The genny broke.
- Yeah. The light broke, everything broke.

1150
01:02:46.011 --> 01:02:49.807
And it was, like, a big deal
because it was a lot of prosthetics...

1151
01:02:49.974 --> 01:02:55.354
...and a lot of stuff for K.N.B.
and it was like middle of the shooting.

1152
01:02:55.521 --> 01:02:58.607
And at the beginning,
the scene was supposed to be...

1153
01:02:58.774 --> 01:03:02.820
...I mean, a little bit bigger.
We have to....

1154
01:03:02.987 --> 01:03:06.907
Okay, but that works,
and people are really cheering...

1155
01:03:07.074 --> 01:03:08.993
...with the dog's attacking
and getting revenge.

1156
01:03:09.159 --> 01:03:13.581
He's the first one of the Carter family
to get, you know, like--

1157
01:03:13.747 --> 01:03:16.041
- Yeah.
- To get revenge...

1158
01:03:16.208 --> 01:03:20.504
...and to fight for them
and stop being a victim.

1159
01:03:21.881 --> 01:03:25.134
That scene was very emotional,
even on set.

1160
01:03:25.301 --> 01:03:29.221
Kathleen asked me at the beginning
just to shoot, like, just a few takes...

1161
01:03:29.388 --> 01:03:33.350
...because she wanted to give a lot,
you know, up front, so....

1162
01:03:33.517 --> 01:03:34.852
And she's amazing.

1163
01:03:35.019 --> 01:03:39.023
I think, yeah, we did only two takes.
And it was great, it was really moving.

1164
01:03:39.189 --> 01:03:41.483
She's wonderful.

1165
01:03:43.903 --> 01:03:46.405
I think you are not using,
in this kind of film...

1166
01:03:46.572 --> 01:03:49.950
...in this kind of horror movie,
to have, like....

1167
01:03:50.117 --> 01:03:55.080
To let the acting be as real as that...

1168
01:03:55.247 --> 01:03:58.042
...and become very emotional.

1169
01:03:58.208 --> 01:04:01.295
You know, as usual, a horror movie
doesn't care about, like--

1170
01:04:01.462 --> 01:04:03.881
They don't care about, like, actors.

1171
01:04:04.048 --> 01:04:08.594
They just want to have violence
and brutal and effects and stuff.

1172
01:04:08.761 --> 01:04:11.555
And I really believe the acting
makes the scare...

1173
01:04:11.722 --> 01:04:13.641
...really much more intense.

1174
01:04:13.807 --> 01:04:16.810
It's so emotional. I remember when
we started doing the violent scenes...

1175
01:04:16.977 --> 01:04:20.189
...it was awful because we'd gotten
to know the family as the Carter family.

1176
01:04:20.356 --> 01:04:22.232
And it seemed like we were
all having fun...

1177
01:04:22.399 --> 01:04:24.860
...then all of a sudden,
we had to start killing them.

1178
01:04:25.027 --> 01:04:28.030
- And it was really, really, hard.
- Yeah, it was, like, very--

1179
01:04:28.197 --> 01:04:31.367
I mean, I was very sad
when Kathleen dies.

1180
01:04:32.159 --> 01:04:33.494
It was like, "Wow."

1181
01:04:33.661 --> 01:04:36.121
You know, that means
that she's not in the movie anymore...

1182
01:04:36.288 --> 01:04:39.625
...and, you know, it was so great
to collaborate with her.

1183
01:04:39.792 --> 01:04:41.835
BOBBY:
They have Catherine, your daughter...

1184
01:04:42.002 --> 01:04:43.712
...and you're gonna sit
and do nothing?!

1185
01:04:43.879 --> 01:04:46.607
COMMENTARY: And here, again,
we are, like, dealing with the contrast.

1186
01:04:46.674 --> 01:04:50.886
Contrast between the silence
and the emotion of her death.

1187
01:04:51.053 --> 01:04:55.140
And then they start fighting
and then they keep silent again...

1188
01:04:55.307 --> 01:04:57.309
...because they heard a noise outside.

1189
01:04:57.476 --> 01:05:00.771
And everything is like that, you know.
You play with the opposite...

1190
01:05:00.938 --> 01:05:06.151
...and with the alternates of,
you know, crazy energy...

1191
01:05:06.318 --> 01:05:10.531
...and then very silent fear
and suspenseful scene.

1192
01:05:11.740 --> 01:05:15.911
That's, I think, the last shot
of Emilie in the film.

1193
01:05:16.078 --> 01:05:18.831
- The last one we shot?
- Yeah. For her, yeah.

1194
01:05:18.998 --> 01:05:20.374
Wow.

1195
01:05:20.541 --> 01:05:23.293
- You're right, you're right. Exactly.
- That was a pretty long day.

1196
01:05:23.460 --> 01:05:25.504
Yeah. Oh, my God.

1197
01:05:25.671 --> 01:05:28.048
That was probably the longest days
we had, 18-hour days.

1198
01:05:28.215 --> 01:05:29.883
- Yeah.
- A couple.

1199
01:05:30.050 --> 01:05:32.369
- Mainly only 12-hour days because the crew...
- Yeah.

1200
01:05:32.469 --> 01:05:34.930
...would really refuse to work
over 12 hours.

1201
01:05:37.224 --> 01:05:38.684
Not that I blame them.

1202
01:05:38.851 --> 01:05:40.936
- Yeah, it was pretty intense.
- It was intense.

1203
01:05:41.103 --> 01:05:43.355
- You know, the heat and the conditions.
- Yeah, yeah.

1204
01:05:43.522 --> 01:05:45.399
It was hard to go over that.

1205
01:05:46.734 --> 01:05:48.944
Very hard.

1206
01:05:57.786 --> 01:06:01.540
We didn't talk about the music,
but tomandandy really, really...

1207
01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:04.918
...you know,
like, improved the movie...

1208
01:06:05.085 --> 01:06:08.589
...and improved the fear
and the emotion by their score.

1209
01:06:08.756 --> 01:06:10.966
I mean, it's amazing.
It's so different.

1210
01:06:11.133 --> 01:06:13.093
Sometimes it's really big
and orchestral...

1211
01:06:13.260 --> 01:06:18.474
...sometimes it's very soft
and orchestral too, but also electronical.

1212
01:06:18.640 --> 01:06:21.060
I mean, they really bring
something to the movie...

1213
01:06:21.226 --> 01:06:25.397
...which is another layer
and another, like....

1214
01:06:26.315 --> 01:06:30.152
It's a kind of voice-over
to the film that really--

1215
01:06:30.319 --> 01:06:32.738
I think they created sounds
I'd never heard before too.

1216
01:06:32.905 --> 01:06:37.534
Yeah, and they managed to be
not too present, to not--

1217
01:06:37.701 --> 01:06:41.413
You know, they are not eclipsing
the story and the Carters...

1218
01:06:41.580 --> 01:06:43.373
...they're just here to underline...

1219
01:06:43.540 --> 01:06:45.959
...all the different emotions
the Carters are going through.

1220
01:06:46.126 --> 01:06:49.338
And as you say, it's great how they start
the movie with something ominous...

1221
01:06:49.505 --> 01:06:54.009
...and after, they slide very softly...

1222
01:06:54.176 --> 01:06:57.137
...onto something much more
orchestral and much more epic.

1223
01:06:57.304 --> 01:06:58.806
Yeah, and epic at the end.

1224
01:06:58.972 --> 01:07:01.892
The music at the end is really huge.
It's like--

1225
01:07:02.059 --> 01:07:05.521
It became like <i>Lord of the Rings</i>,
how you said. And it's very good.

1226
01:07:05.687 --> 01:07:09.024
But it's cool because it expresses
really the dark journeys, in fact.

1227
01:07:09.191 --> 01:07:13.403
Yeah, it's following what Doug Bukowski
is going through, you know, from--

1228
01:07:13.570 --> 01:07:15.405
- His emotional journey.
- Yeah.

1229
01:07:15.572 --> 01:07:19.076
But tomandandy are wonderful.
Did a great job.

1230
01:07:22.412 --> 01:07:24.665
Their instincts were really perfect.

1231
01:07:24.873 --> 01:07:28.293
[BABY CRYING OVER WALKIE-TALKIE]

1232
01:07:29.419 --> 01:07:31.505
COMMENTARY:
That's my hands.

1233
01:07:31.672 --> 01:07:35.008
I was shooting, like, Big Bob
coming back to the gas station...

1234
01:07:35.175 --> 01:07:37.469
...and second unit was on
the other side of the road.

1235
01:07:37.636 --> 01:07:40.139
That was amazing, I got the chance
to shoot with the director.

1236
01:07:40.305 --> 01:07:44.017
Yeah, and I ran from the first set
because Aaron wasn't here.

1237
01:07:44.184 --> 01:07:46.270
I ran from the first set
to give my hand...

1238
01:07:46.436 --> 01:07:49.940
...because we are looking
quite the same, Aaron and I.

1239
01:07:50.107 --> 01:07:52.484
Which wasn't meant on purpose,
by the way.

1240
01:07:52.651 --> 01:07:55.821
And I did his hand,
and I was very proud...

1241
01:07:56.155 --> 01:07:58.740
...to be able to play
the Aaron Stanford hand.

1242
01:07:58.907 --> 01:08:02.119
Sometimes on set
we would confuse Aaron and Alex.

1243
01:08:02.536 --> 01:08:05.581
We'd walk up behind Alex
and say "Aaron" and vice versa.

1244
01:08:05.747 --> 01:08:09.835
Well, we just saw the dissolve between
his close-up and the sun rising.

1245
01:08:10.002 --> 01:08:13.755
It's nice also because you saw
the light on the side of his face.

1246
01:08:13.922 --> 01:08:18.552
And the sun is coming and the light of
the sun becomes the light on his face...

1247
01:08:18.719 --> 01:08:22.848
...which isn't real. The light of
the campfire, it's the same color.

1248
01:08:23.015 --> 01:08:25.601
And that's the last shot of the film.

1249
01:08:25.767 --> 01:08:27.352
- Exactly the last one.
- Oh, my God.

1250
01:08:27.519 --> 01:08:30.606
The close-up of the ants
on the blood.

1251
01:08:30.772 --> 01:08:33.734
It's the last, last shot
on the film in Marrakech.

1252
01:08:33.901 --> 01:08:37.070
It's funny, because all this part
was shot close to Marrakech...

1253
01:08:37.237 --> 01:08:38.780
...the three last days
of the shooting.

1254
01:08:38.947 --> 01:08:42.659
But it's funny because all
the locations are very remote.

1255
01:08:42.826 --> 01:08:48.040
The first location where you see
dogs running through the hills...

1256
01:08:48.207 --> 01:08:52.211
...another location where you see
the vulture and also the mine.

1257
01:08:52.377 --> 01:08:54.396
- Nothing is linked, yeah.
- Nothing is linked...

1258
01:08:54.463 --> 01:08:58.467
-...but it works very, very well.
- Yeah, you felt a continuity in the site.

1259
01:08:58.634 --> 01:09:02.763
That mine is a salt mine
just like 50 minutes...

1260
01:09:03.347 --> 01:09:05.807
...one hour out Marrakech.

1261
01:09:06.099 --> 01:09:10.646
And it's a place-- Nobody shot here
before, and it's amazing, it's huge.

1262
01:09:11.355 --> 01:09:15.317
It's exactly the place.
We didn't touch the location.

1263
01:09:15.484 --> 01:09:22.366
The only thing is Joseph, like, prepared
for us the graveyard of the miner.

1264
01:09:22.532 --> 01:09:24.034
The first cut we did,
it was funny...

1265
01:09:24.201 --> 01:09:28.622
...because we open the door and we see
this corridor, as you see right now...

1266
01:09:28.789 --> 01:09:32.000
...but we didn't have light.
Nothing, so we couldn't go further.

1267
01:09:32.167 --> 01:09:34.962
- It's right after when--
- We came back that we discovered that.

1268
01:09:35.128 --> 01:09:38.090
We discovered what we got inside
this huge cave.

1269
01:09:38.257 --> 01:09:40.759
- To me, it looks like a huge set.
- It really does.

1270
01:09:40.926 --> 01:09:44.930
Yeah, and it's amazing
because it's so real. And it's so--

1271
01:09:45.097 --> 01:09:46.890
In fact, it's very easy to shoot inside.

1272
01:09:47.057 --> 01:09:48.767
- It was fine.
- Yeah, it was great.

1273
01:09:48.934 --> 01:09:50.811
- There were a lot of bats.
- Yeah, millions.

1274
01:09:50.978 --> 01:09:53.146
Millions of bats. And bat droppings.

1275
01:09:54.147 --> 01:09:56.984
But this was cool. This was so
much cooler than being outside.

1276
01:09:57.150 --> 01:09:59.903
Yeah, but you felt the salt in the air.

1277
01:10:00.070 --> 01:10:02.990
- You could pick salt off the wall.
- Yeah.

1278
01:10:06.368 --> 01:10:08.870
It's a working salt mine.

1279
01:10:09.037 --> 01:10:10.831
That was a great find.

1280
01:10:10.998 --> 01:10:13.917
Oh, I'm happy that shot is back.

1281
01:10:14.084 --> 01:10:17.212
I forgot that we bring back that shot.
I'm very happy.

1282
01:10:17.379 --> 01:10:20.716
You know, we cut that for questions
of rhythm in the movie...

1283
01:10:20.882 --> 01:10:22.968
...and we bring it back for the DVD.

1284
01:10:23.135 --> 01:10:25.470
I think it's a good shot
to establish a little bit more...

1285
01:10:25.637 --> 01:10:27.639
...the graveyard of the miner.

1286
01:10:42.112 --> 01:10:44.990
And also that location
is really a blessing...

1287
01:10:45.157 --> 01:10:50.495
...because it's quite easy to access,
so it's quite easy to bring a crane in.

1288
01:10:50.662 --> 01:10:53.707
And here, like, to do,
like, a shot like that...

1289
01:10:53.874 --> 01:10:58.337
...in this kind of mine, it's not so easy.
It's, like, almost impossible as usual.

1290
01:10:58.503 --> 01:11:03.467
And here, I mean, you know,
everything was waiting for us, in fact.

1291
01:11:03.633 --> 01:11:07.387
It was really the perfect location and
the perfect place to make that movie.

1292
01:11:07.554 --> 01:11:10.766
And that's really, like--
You know, I don't know...

1293
01:11:10.932 --> 01:11:15.312
...like three hours
from the place we just left.

1294
01:11:15.479 --> 01:11:17.856
It's funny, that's three hours
from the place we left...

1295
01:11:18.023 --> 01:11:20.859
...that's where they fight at the end,
that's another location.

1296
01:11:21.026 --> 01:11:25.072
And that, his POV,
is gonna be other location.

1297
01:11:25.238 --> 01:11:28.742
So everything is removed by,
like, at least 200 kilometers.

1298
01:11:28.909 --> 01:11:30.494
[COMMENTATOR CHUCKLES]

1299
01:11:33.121 --> 01:11:36.541
Once again, Jamison Goei,
who supervised all the CG...

1300
01:11:36.708 --> 01:11:41.004
...made an amazing job for the town
that we can see here.

1301
01:11:41.171 --> 01:11:44.841
Jamison and Laura did a wonderful job
on the visual effects.

1302
01:11:47.469 --> 01:11:52.265
What we decide also for-- With Maxime,
the DP, is to start the movie...

1303
01:11:52.432 --> 01:11:59.272
...using 100 ASA film stock
and then, by night, using, like, 500 ASA.

1304
01:11:59.439 --> 01:12:04.277
And then for the third act, for all
the next day, in fact, using 250...

1305
01:12:04.444 --> 01:12:10.575
...but also doing
the 45-degrees shutter effect...

1306
01:12:10.742 --> 01:12:14.830
...which makes everything
look a little bit, like, strange.

1307
01:12:14.996 --> 01:12:18.083
All the movements
are a little bit different, a little bit off.

1308
01:12:18.250 --> 01:12:22.671
I remember we didn't tell
to the editor that and he was in Paris...

1309
01:12:22.838 --> 01:12:24.673
...and as I said, he freaks out.

1310
01:12:24.840 --> 01:12:27.217
He calls and he says,
"Hey, there is something wrong.

1311
01:12:27.384 --> 01:12:30.429
Everything is, like, faster or slower,
I don't know.

1312
01:12:30.595 --> 01:12:33.932
There is, like, a kind of strange effect
on all the frames, you know?"

1313
01:12:34.099 --> 01:12:38.437
As soon as you see some particle
or fire or element fly in the wind...

1314
01:12:38.603 --> 01:12:42.190
...you can feel the difference
of the 45-degree shutter effect.

1315
01:12:42.357 --> 01:12:45.026
- And you forgot to tell Baxter?
- Yeah.

1316
01:12:45.193 --> 01:12:47.154
But it's funny
because when he told us that...

1317
01:12:47.320 --> 01:12:49.781
...you know, we forgot also
that we used that.

1318
01:12:49.948 --> 01:12:52.451
We don't forget, but we didn't
understand what he was saying.

1319
01:12:52.617 --> 01:12:54.411
He didn't know that, so it was like:

1320
01:12:54.578 --> 01:12:56.413
"Okay, something's wrong,
something's wrong."

1321
01:12:56.580 --> 01:12:58.957
So it was, like, a huge crisis on set.

1322
01:12:59.124 --> 01:13:01.793
We did have a crisis, though, with it.
What was the crisis we had?

1323
01:13:01.960 --> 01:13:03.670
No, the crisis was with the light.

1324
01:13:03.837 --> 01:13:05.964
- Some light reflecting.
- That was it.

1325
01:13:06.131 --> 01:13:08.008
Which you couldn't see
by the naked eye.

1326
01:13:08.175 --> 01:13:10.135
Yeah, that was a big deal.

1327
01:13:10.302 --> 01:13:12.345
That was a bit of a crisis,
we had to reshoot.

1328
01:13:12.512 --> 01:13:14.222
Yeah, that we didn't use.

1329
01:13:14.431 --> 01:13:15.599
Ai-yi-yi-

1330
01:13:15.765 --> 01:13:17.017
[COMMENTATORS LAUGHING]

1331
01:13:17.184 --> 01:13:19.478
- I mean, that's good. That's life.
- Okay.

1332
01:13:19.644 --> 01:13:22.147
We didn't have to reshoot as much
as we thought we'd have to.

1333
01:13:22.314 --> 01:13:24.107
No, we didn't reshoot-- I mean....

1334
01:13:24.274 --> 01:13:27.110
There is, well, like,
principal photography, and that's it.

1335
01:13:27.277 --> 01:13:32.115
I remember being in-- Before prep,
with all of you guys saying:

1336
01:13:32.449 --> 01:13:35.076
"You know, in Hollywood,
you have to reshoot, that's the rule."

1337
01:13:35.243 --> 01:13:37.120
- That's true.
- Everyone reshoots.

1338
01:13:37.287 --> 01:13:39.289
- Everyone do some--
- Absolutely.

1339
01:13:39.456 --> 01:13:40.499
And we didn't.

1340
01:13:40.665 --> 01:13:43.376
I don't know that I've worked
on a movie where we didn't reshoot...

1341
01:13:43.543 --> 01:13:44.794
...I think, other than <i>Scream</i>.

1342
01:13:44.961 --> 01:13:47.797
I think I've had to go back and reshoot
on every movie I've worked on.

1343
01:13:47.964 --> 01:13:50.759
Yeah, and we were pretty--
Not "sure," I won't say that.

1344
01:13:50.926 --> 01:13:52.511
But we were pretty, like, confident...

1345
01:13:52.677 --> 01:13:55.472
...that we would have enough material
to do the movie.

1346
01:13:55.639 --> 01:13:57.641
I guess the American version is
that you test it.

1347
01:13:57.807 --> 01:13:59.684
And if you need to reshoot,
you reshoot.

1348
01:13:59.851 --> 01:14:02.437
Luckily we did, we tested it,
and we didn't need to reshoot.

1349
01:14:02.604 --> 01:14:04.648
- It was great.
- That was great, yeah.

1350
01:14:04.814 --> 01:14:06.149
It was great news.

1351
01:14:06.316 --> 01:14:08.610
Those two, like, test screenings
were, like, amazing.

1352
01:14:08.777 --> 01:14:10.737
Maybe one of the best days in my life.

1353
01:14:11.363 --> 01:14:12.864
- The first or the second?
- Both.

1354
01:14:13.031 --> 01:14:17.244
- Both of them. They were love letters.
- Yeah, it was, like, so big victory.

1355
01:14:17.410 --> 01:14:19.120
- It was exciting.
- It was huge, yeah.

1356
01:14:19.287 --> 01:14:21.248
- It was a long road.
- It was a long road.

1357
01:14:21.414 --> 01:14:23.124
- Long road.
- Yeah.

1358
01:14:23.291 --> 01:14:24.626
We fought the good fight.

1359
01:14:24.793 --> 01:14:28.463
And here-- I mean, here I have to
thank you, Marianne...

1360
01:14:28.630 --> 01:14:32.008
...because you're really the one that
trusted us about the size of that town.

1361
01:14:32.175 --> 01:14:35.554
You know, it was so crazy
to build all the different houses...

1362
01:14:35.720 --> 01:14:39.933
...with all that mannequins coming from
U.S. with all the furniture to build.

1363
01:14:40.100 --> 01:14:43.562
- It was, like, so expensive as a set.
- Yeah, all this furniture was built.

1364
01:14:43.728 --> 01:14:46.314
Because in Morocco
they couldn't find '50s furniture...

1365
01:14:46.481 --> 01:14:49.192
...so the set-decorating department
built all of this furniture.

1366
01:14:49.359 --> 01:14:51.570
Everything was built.

1367
01:14:51.736 --> 01:14:55.574
And we knew that all that part of
the movie which is not in the original...

1368
01:14:55.740 --> 01:14:58.743
...all that third act
which is not in the original film...

1369
01:14:58.910 --> 01:15:03.623
...were, like, being the center and
the climax of our new <i>Hills Have Eyes</i>.

1370
01:15:03.790 --> 01:15:05.625
The details are amazing,
like that wallpaper.

1371
01:15:05.792 --> 01:15:08.378
All the wallpaper Joseph chose
is vintage wallpaper.

1372
01:15:08.545 --> 01:15:10.380
I mean, he really looked
long and hard...

1373
01:15:10.547 --> 01:15:12.215
...to make sure every detail
was perfect.

1374
01:15:12.382 --> 01:15:14.551
And the mannequins
were made for us...

1375
01:15:14.718 --> 01:15:18.179
...according to mannequins from the
'50s that they used in this test village.

1376
01:15:18.346 --> 01:15:23.018
And all the car from the '50s are coming,
like, from different places in Morocco.

1377
01:15:23.184 --> 01:15:27.230
You know, like, special shipment
to Ouarzazate.

1378
01:15:27.397 --> 01:15:28.732
Just to find all that wardrobe...

1379
01:15:28.898 --> 01:15:32.694
...and, you know, age all that wardrobe.
And the detail is amazing.

1380
01:15:32.861 --> 01:15:34.404
Joseph really did a great job.

1381
01:15:34.571 --> 01:15:39.117
And the music here also reminds the
feeling of the Sergio Leone Western...

1382
01:15:39.284 --> 01:15:42.537
...with the electric guitar and stuff.
Tomandandy were great here...

1383
01:15:42.704 --> 01:15:45.415
...because they really get
what we tried to do behind.

1384
01:15:45.582 --> 01:15:48.043
And Doug's journey,
his heroic journey.

1385
01:15:48.209 --> 01:15:52.297
This set is the biggest set in our movie,
and it was just behind the studio.

1386
01:15:52.464 --> 01:15:54.633
Like one kilometer
behind the studio.

1387
01:15:54.799 --> 01:15:59.971
And it was funny for us, coming from
the low budget, to have this huge set...

1388
01:16:00.138 --> 01:16:02.891
...where we'd shot, like, just
two days and a half, or three days.

1389
01:16:03.058 --> 01:16:04.993
- No, more, more. Three days.
- For the outside.

1390
01:16:05.060 --> 01:16:07.228
For the outside is three days.

1391
01:16:07.395 --> 01:16:10.440
Inside the Big Brain house
is like four, five days.

1392
01:16:10.607 --> 01:16:13.276
And Big Mama house was the--

1393
01:16:13.443 --> 01:16:16.488
Was including the three days
because it's on set.

1394
01:16:16.655 --> 01:16:20.283
But it's-- You know, it's like--
Joseph did a so amazing job.

1395
01:16:20.450 --> 01:16:25.163
Joseph Nemec, the production designer.
He was really tough with all his crew.

1396
01:16:25.622 --> 01:16:27.582
- Oh, man.
- He was really, like, behind them...

1397
01:16:27.749 --> 01:16:29.918
...all the time,
but you can really feel--

1398
01:16:30.085 --> 01:16:33.963
And I think it's one
of the best craftwork he did ever.

1399
01:16:34.130 --> 01:16:36.841
I do too. I think it's beautiful.
And he did an amazing job.

1400
01:16:37.008 --> 01:16:38.385
And he had so many challenges.

1401
01:16:38.551 --> 01:16:42.347
The language, just finding props
and things, you know, in Morocco. He--

1402
01:16:42.514 --> 01:16:44.115
- He never give up.
- He never gave up.

1403
01:16:44.182 --> 01:16:47.143
And the colors are so beautiful
in the movie.

1404
01:16:47.519 --> 01:16:49.788
- His color theme is amazing.
- Here also you can see...

1405
01:16:49.854 --> 01:16:53.066
...the hills on the back of the shot,
not on the frame.

1406
01:16:53.233 --> 01:16:56.611
All the hills are, like,
added by Jamison in CGI.

1407
01:16:56.778 --> 01:16:59.280
Yeah, all the hills were added.

1408
01:17:00.198 --> 01:17:02.742
CGI picked them out.

1409
01:17:02.909 --> 01:17:05.328
Joseph had a blast here
designing these different houses.

1410
01:17:05.495 --> 01:17:09.249
Yeah, and everything, also, you feel
the wind and you feel the dust...

1411
01:17:09.416 --> 01:17:11.000
...but it's always like that.

1412
01:17:11.167 --> 01:17:14.421
You know, when you need the dust and
we need the wind, you don't have it.

1413
01:17:14.587 --> 01:17:18.007
So we were on set
with two huge wind machines...

1414
01:17:18.174 --> 01:17:20.260
...and everything was shot
with the wind machines...

1415
01:17:20.427 --> 01:17:24.264
...which make like 100-decibel sound
all the time...

1416
01:17:24.431 --> 01:17:27.225
...so it was almost impossible
to communicate with the actors...

1417
01:17:27.392 --> 01:17:30.228
...and with, you know, Aaron Stanford
when we were shooting...

1418
01:17:30.395 --> 01:17:32.647
...because the wind was so strong...

1419
01:17:32.814 --> 01:17:35.984
...and the sound was so strong
that you were just like....

1420
01:17:36.151 --> 01:17:37.694
It was nightmare
because of the heat...

1421
01:17:37.861 --> 01:17:41.781
...but not only that. Because also of
the sound of the wind machines all day.

1422
01:17:45.535 --> 01:17:50.582
All that part of the film where he's going
inside the house to take the baby...

1423
01:17:50.749 --> 01:17:57.213
...and then be knocked off
by Big Mama was added during prep.

1424
01:17:57.380 --> 01:18:00.884
We came with the idea of that scene,
which wasn't on the first draft...

1425
01:18:01.050 --> 01:18:03.678
...and then the icebox, also, scene...

1426
01:18:03.845 --> 01:18:08.308
...came, like, really during the prep
on location, rewriting the script.

1427
01:18:08.475 --> 01:18:11.895
We realized that we needed Doug,
like, a big hope.

1428
01:18:12.061 --> 01:18:14.481
I mean, that he'd found the baby.
That was very important.

1429
01:18:14.647 --> 01:18:16.583
- To have another step.
- To have another step.

1430
01:18:16.649 --> 01:18:19.569
You think he's going to manage
to get the baby...

1431
01:18:19.736 --> 01:18:24.115
...and at the last moment you get
a big jump and he's hit by Big Mama.

1432
01:18:24.282 --> 01:18:26.868
The actress who's playing Big Mama,
agree on--

1433
01:18:27.035 --> 01:18:30.997
She's Italian, German, whatever.
And--

1434
01:18:31.164 --> 01:18:32.499
Lives in Casablanca.

1435
01:18:32.665 --> 01:18:35.502
And she was living in Casablanca
and she came...

1436
01:18:35.668 --> 01:18:37.879
-...and she agree on shaving her head.
- For $1000.

1437
01:18:38.046 --> 01:18:39.756
[COMMENTATOR LAUGHING]

1438
01:18:39.923 --> 01:18:42.383
- That was like, "Wow."
- But she's so great.

1439
01:18:42.550 --> 01:18:44.636
Yeah, and she was very happy
to play in the movie.

1440
01:18:44.803 --> 01:18:48.097
And she's an actress, so she's doing
a lot of film shooting over there.

1441
01:18:48.264 --> 01:18:50.241
- She's not, like, only doing that.
- No, no, no.

1442
01:18:50.308 --> 01:18:53.394
But she was great, she totally
was thrilled to have her hair cut off.

1443
01:18:53.561 --> 01:18:56.981
And I think she just did a great job.
I think that mutant is really interesting.

1444
01:18:57.148 --> 01:19:00.235
- And she had a lot of fun as well.
- She was wonderful. She loved the baby.

1445
01:19:00.401 --> 01:19:02.946
It was so weird seeing her holding
the baby at the commissary.

1446
01:19:03.112 --> 01:19:04.447
Yeah.

1447
01:19:06.950 --> 01:19:08.451
[BABY SCREAMS]

1448
01:19:10.411 --> 01:19:13.540
COMMENTARY: We used the
opportunity of those flashes...

1449
01:19:13.706 --> 01:19:17.794
...to put back some shots that we love
that were not in the movie...

1450
01:19:17.961 --> 01:19:20.255
...but tell the story. It's kind of like:

1451
01:19:20.421 --> 01:19:23.091
"What will be the POV
of the baby being...

1452
01:19:23.258 --> 01:19:25.885
...you know,
carried from houses to houses?"

1453
01:19:28.096 --> 01:19:30.640
They are doing the trap.

1454
01:19:42.569 --> 01:19:48.992
That smiling baby-shaker was,
like, so, so funny, so...

1455
01:19:49.826 --> 01:19:52.161
And that's also, like,
one of the good surprise...

1456
01:19:52.328 --> 01:19:55.540
...when you are shooting only
in split days...

1457
01:19:55.707 --> 01:19:58.585
...is, of course, every day
the sunset.

1458
01:19:58.751 --> 01:20:01.963
And the sun setting exactly
in front of the Carter vehicle...

1459
01:20:02.130 --> 01:20:06.009
...so you have an amazing light
coming just behind the Carters.

1460
01:20:06.175 --> 01:20:09.637
And so you can have
this beautiful backlit--

1461
01:20:09.804 --> 01:20:11.180
Kind of magic-hour moments.

1462
01:20:11.347 --> 01:20:12.932
- It's not even--
- Before.

1463
01:20:13.099 --> 01:20:15.768
Yeah, it's before.
And you see the silhouette...

1464
01:20:15.935 --> 01:20:18.563
...and that brings
really something desperate.

1465
01:20:18.730 --> 01:20:23.359
And with this 45-degree shutter effect,
you can really feel...

1466
01:20:23.526 --> 01:20:27.155
...you know, like, the hair,
like, blowing in the wind.

1467
01:20:30.950 --> 01:20:32.535
We had a lot of fun
doing that scene...

1468
01:20:32.702 --> 01:20:36.205
...because we used, like,
special equipment for the camera...

1469
01:20:36.372 --> 01:20:40.251
...which allowed us to go 360 degrees
inside with the lens.

1470
01:20:40.418 --> 01:20:42.086
And it's a crane shot, in fact...

1471
01:20:42.253 --> 01:20:44.881
...but we are not using the crane
for the crane...

1472
01:20:45.048 --> 01:20:49.552
...but just to be really inside the box,
the icebox, with Aaron.

1473
01:20:49.719 --> 01:20:53.389
And so Aaron is really like--
It's really closed. He's really in the box.

1474
01:20:53.556 --> 01:20:56.434
We also had a little crisis because
we didn't have enough body parts...

1475
01:20:56.601 --> 01:20:59.979
-...for the scene.
- Some body parts are from <i>Hostel</i>.

1476
01:21:00.146 --> 01:21:02.607
- Oh, yeah.
- I saw them in <i>Hostel</i>.

1477
01:21:02.815 --> 01:21:03.858
[COMMENTATORS LAUGHING]

1478
01:21:04.025 --> 01:21:07.654
I recognized some arms
and stuff from K.N.B. from <i>Hostel</i>.

1479
01:21:07.820 --> 01:21:10.114
Yeah, some of them were,
but not enough arrived...

1480
01:21:10.281 --> 01:21:13.034
...so I called <i>The Ten Commandments</i>
to see if they had extra parts.

1481
01:21:13.201 --> 01:21:15.328
- I was calling--
- Yeah, but that was not so good.

1482
01:21:15.495 --> 01:21:17.205
- They weren't so good.
- Not well made.

1483
01:21:17.372 --> 01:21:21.584
At the end of the day, we used mainly
all the K.N.B. body parts that we found.

1484
01:21:21.751 --> 01:21:23.836
- We had a lot of blood.
- Yeah.

1485
01:21:24.003 --> 01:21:25.672
We cut up a lot of mannequins.

1486
01:21:25.838 --> 01:21:28.341
It's true. Like,
some box was supposed to come...

1487
01:21:28.508 --> 01:21:30.426
-...from <i>Hostel</i>--
- That's it.

1488
01:21:30.885 --> 01:21:33.388
They arrived,
but it was only a small box.

1489
01:21:33.554 --> 01:21:38.101
No, remember, they put on the box
"arms," which means...

1490
01:21:38.267 --> 01:21:40.228
-"Weapon" in French.
-..."weapon" in French.

1491
01:21:40.395 --> 01:21:42.313
So in Morocco,
they received this box--

1492
01:21:42.480 --> 01:21:44.440
- They blocked the box.
- They blocked the box...

1493
01:21:44.607 --> 01:21:48.111
...and we couldn't be able to have it.

1494
01:21:48.403 --> 01:21:50.029
[DOG BARKING]

1495
01:21:54.826 --> 01:21:57.954
COMMENTARY: Greg loved, with
second unit, doing some dog stuff.

1496
01:21:58.329 --> 01:22:00.665
- It's amazing.
- Those dogs are great.

1497
01:22:00.832 --> 01:22:05.545
It was not so easy. It looks very easy
on-screen like that, but wow.

1498
01:22:05.712 --> 01:22:07.505
The German shepherds
were like a nightmare.

1499
01:22:07.672 --> 01:22:11.926
At one point, I remember
the dog trainer coming to me and saying:

1500
01:22:12.093 --> 01:22:15.096
"You know what? German shepherds
are not the best dogs to be trained."

1501
01:22:15.263 --> 01:22:16.639
Which is so stupid.

1502
01:22:16.806 --> 01:22:20.768
I mean, look, German shepherds
are the best dogs to train.

1503
01:22:20.935 --> 01:22:24.105
It took a lot of work, but in the end,
I think their performance is amazing.

1504
01:22:24.272 --> 01:22:27.400
- It's a big surprise.
- Not really a lack of preparation.

1505
01:22:27.567 --> 01:22:29.110
- A lot of footage.
- Yeah.

1506
01:22:29.277 --> 01:22:31.154
A lot of shooting.

1507
01:22:38.453 --> 01:22:41.080
BIG BRAIN [SINGING]:
<i>O say, can you</i>--

1508
01:22:41.247 --> 01:22:43.124
COMMENTARY:
This location, I mean--

1509
01:22:43.291 --> 01:22:46.919
Joseph really, like,
built an amazing set here.

1510
01:22:47.086 --> 01:22:49.213
It's-- Everything is on-stage.

1511
01:22:49.380 --> 01:22:51.799
It's so specific.
I mean, look at the design there.

1512
01:22:51.966 --> 01:22:54.469
And, you know, you see a lot
of mannequins here and there.

1513
01:22:54.635 --> 01:22:57.680
And previously you saw a lot
of mannequins in this town...

1514
01:22:57.889 --> 01:23:02.101
...but in fact, we are only working
with 16 mannequins.

1515
01:23:02.268 --> 01:23:04.203
- We had to keep moving them around.
- Exactly.

1516
01:23:04.270 --> 01:23:06.731
- And redressing.
- Until we destroyed them, all of them...

1517
01:23:06.898 --> 01:23:08.858
...with the ax.

1518
01:23:12.570 --> 01:23:14.947
- Big Brain.
- Yeah.

1519
01:23:15.114 --> 01:23:17.533
- And his family.
- Yeah, Desmond Askew is like--

1520
01:23:17.700 --> 01:23:21.037
It's like, you know, nobody can
recognize him with all the makeup...

1521
01:23:21.204 --> 01:23:24.457
...but he really-- And I remember
when we were, like, casting the movie...

1522
01:23:24.624 --> 01:23:29.587
...it was just about the position
and being able to play in that position...

1523
01:23:29.754 --> 01:23:33.424
...with your eye open.
It was really about that.

1524
01:23:33.591 --> 01:23:36.677
And being able also to have that voice,
that very asthmatic voice.

1525
01:23:36.844 --> 01:23:41.224
The voice was one of
the main things to-- For this character.

1526
01:23:41.390 --> 01:23:44.477
And Desmond has this great voice.

1527
01:23:45.394 --> 01:23:47.105
DOUG:
Answer me.

1528
01:23:47.647 --> 01:23:50.650
I don't know where she is.

1529
01:23:50.817 --> 01:23:53.027
COMMENTARY:
It's very tricky as a scene...

1530
01:23:53.194 --> 01:23:55.755
...because Big Brain is supposed
to give a lot of information...

1531
01:23:55.822 --> 01:23:57.698
...on the background of the story...

1532
01:23:57.865 --> 01:24:01.661
...and why they are acting like that
and what's happened in this place.

1533
01:24:01.828 --> 01:24:04.163
And in the same time,
you don't have, like--

1534
01:24:04.330 --> 01:24:09.877
You don't want, as an audience member,
to stop and, you know, like, be--

1535
01:24:10.044 --> 01:24:13.923
Teach, like, why everything
is happening like that.

1536
01:24:14.090 --> 01:24:17.218
So you have to keep the tension
and to keep the action following...

1537
01:24:17.385 --> 01:24:19.345
...even if he's talking about that.

1538
01:24:19.554 --> 01:24:22.223
BIG BRAIN:
--and turned everything to ashes.

1539
01:24:23.224 --> 01:24:25.309
COMMENTARY:
I remember giving, like, a picture of...

1540
01:24:25.476 --> 01:24:28.813
...<i>The Changeling</i> wheelchair
to Joseph...

1541
01:24:28.980 --> 01:24:31.440
-...for the wheelchair of Big Brain.
- That's right.

1542
01:24:31.649 --> 01:24:33.943
Yeah, that's great.

1543
01:24:34.819 --> 01:24:37.405
I'm impressed of Greg Nicotero's
work on the characters' teeth.

1544
01:24:37.572 --> 01:24:38.698
- Me too.
- You can really--

1545
01:24:38.865 --> 01:24:41.284
- You don't feel that it's fake.
- No.

1546
01:24:41.450 --> 01:24:44.203
And everything was made different
for each of the characters.

1547
01:24:44.370 --> 01:24:49.584
And it's really giving--
Bring like half of the makeup.

1548
01:24:50.126 --> 01:24:52.211
Here comes Pluto.
This is my favorite scene.

1549
01:24:52.378 --> 01:24:54.964
And here it's amazing
because it's really, like, real.

1550
01:24:55.131 --> 01:24:57.341
I mean, Michael Bailey Smith did
everything here.

1551
01:24:57.508 --> 01:25:01.262
- And Florian was the--
- The stunt double for Aaron.

1552
01:25:01.470 --> 01:25:03.681
The stunt double
is doing an amazing job.

1553
01:25:03.848 --> 01:25:05.224
- He's incredible.
- Yeah.

1554
01:25:05.391 --> 01:25:08.853
And everything was made really, like,
you know, very--

1555
01:25:09.020 --> 01:25:14.233
It's like four, five days of shooting, but
it's so big. There is so much going on.

1556
01:25:14.400 --> 01:25:19.238
And for all the gags,
you don't have, like, a second take.

1557
01:25:19.697 --> 01:25:23.743
It's very hard. Because each time,
it's like a lot of prep, a lot of--

1558
01:25:23.910 --> 01:25:27.538
To rebuild and to redo everything.

1559
01:25:36.505 --> 01:25:40.426
But that's really our favorite moment
in the film. I mean, that fight.

1560
01:25:40.593 --> 01:25:43.679
The Pluto-Doug fight, it's absolutely
my favorite.

1561
01:25:43.846 --> 01:25:46.724
It wasn't so easy to convince you
that we needed so much time to do it.

1562
01:25:46.891 --> 01:25:49.393
Oh, I think I was saying yes
to everything, wasn't I?

1563
01:25:49.560 --> 01:25:52.521
Yeah. At the end, yeah,
you said yes to everything.

1564
01:25:52.688 --> 01:25:54.065
You know, I mean, on the script...

1565
01:25:54.232 --> 01:25:56.067
-...it's only three pages.
- No, you're right.

1566
01:25:56.234 --> 01:25:58.085
- It's true, it's true.
- Three pages means--

1567
01:25:58.152 --> 01:26:00.571
You know, like,
according to the American model...

1568
01:26:00.738 --> 01:26:03.157
...means like a day and a half
of shooting.

1569
01:26:03.324 --> 01:26:07.536
And to do a scene like that, it's really,
really four, five days minimum.

1570
01:26:07.703 --> 01:26:11.540
It's true. It's such a beautiful scene.
How many days did we shoot this?

1571
01:26:11.707 --> 01:26:14.585
I know how many first-unit days.
How many second-unit days?

1572
01:26:14.752 --> 01:26:17.129
- Not so much.
- No, no, we stayed together, in fact.

1573
01:26:17.296 --> 01:26:19.215
- We didn't split for--
- I know it was-- Yeah.

1574
01:26:19.382 --> 01:26:21.801
So would you say, like,
10 second-unit days?

1575
01:26:21.968 --> 01:26:23.344
- No. For all the film?
- Yeah.

1576
01:26:23.511 --> 01:26:25.054
Yeah. All the film is 15.

1577
01:26:25.263 --> 01:26:27.056
That's what I thought. So 45 and 15.

1578
01:26:27.265 --> 01:26:29.684
- Yeah, 60.
- Not bad. What you said you needed.

1579
01:26:29.850 --> 01:26:30.893
Exactly.

1580
01:26:31.060 --> 01:26:32.103
[COMMENTATOR LAUGHING]

1581
01:26:32.270 --> 01:26:34.105
I come back to the average
of film stock.

1582
01:26:34.272 --> 01:26:37.900
I said the average
and the number of shooting days.

1583
01:26:41.237 --> 01:26:44.365
So many gags back together,
you know. It's like he--

1584
01:26:44.532 --> 01:26:47.159
When you are shooting that,
you get very excited on writing...

1585
01:26:47.326 --> 01:26:48.786
...so you add and add and add.

1586
01:26:49.203 --> 01:26:51.831
And then when you are shooting,
you say, "Oh, that's too much."

1587
01:26:51.998 --> 01:26:55.501
I mean, we're, like, just hearing
the story about it and we need to go--

1588
01:26:55.668 --> 01:27:01.007
We have like 100 pages to come.
It's never end. Never end.

1589
01:27:01.173 --> 01:27:03.467
I think that's--
I never had that feeling before.

1590
01:27:03.634 --> 01:27:05.094
Like, to be in the scene...

1591
01:27:05.261 --> 01:27:07.638
...and feeling that you will
never finish the scene...

1592
01:27:07.805 --> 01:27:09.473
...because it's so big,
it's so ambitious.

1593
01:27:09.640 --> 01:27:11.892
- So much ahead.
- Yeah.

1594
01:27:12.059 --> 01:27:16.439
Because we are using prosthetics,
we are using a little bit CG...

1595
01:27:16.605 --> 01:27:19.900
...we are using wire for the stunts.
We are using-- I mean--

1596
01:27:20.067 --> 01:27:22.778
- Dogs.
- Dogs. I mean, it's...

1597
01:27:24.030 --> 01:27:27.575
So here, once again,
I'm thinking about the stuntman...

1598
01:27:27.742 --> 01:27:32.621
...because you have to imagine Michael
Bailey Smith was an ex-Dallas Cowboy...

1599
01:27:32.830 --> 01:27:34.999
- Football player.
-...football player.

1600
01:27:35.166 --> 01:27:38.502
So you have to imagine,
when he goes through the wall--

1601
01:27:38.669 --> 01:27:42.340
- And against him.
- Against him, it's like...

1602
01:27:42.548 --> 01:27:44.633
- It's real. It's not fake.
- He's huge.

1603
01:27:44.800 --> 01:27:48.554
And here, I mean, the cut fingers were
also a big deal with the MPAA...

1604
01:27:48.721 --> 01:27:50.806
...because it was made in
a very real way.

1605
01:27:52.141 --> 01:27:53.893
The first shot is made
with prosthetics...

1606
01:27:54.060 --> 01:27:57.521
...and the other shot is made with
green finger, which, you know, like...

1607
01:27:58.356 --> 01:28:00.149
...then you erase.
So he can turn his hand...

1608
01:28:00.316 --> 01:28:03.861
...and you really have a feeling
that his fingers are cut.

1609
01:28:09.575 --> 01:28:13.287
Of course, one of our main influence
here is the <i>True  Romance</i> scene...

1610
01:28:13.454 --> 01:28:16.332
...between Patricia Arquette
and the Mob guy...

1611
01:28:16.499 --> 01:28:21.504
...you know, like, fighting. It's really,
like, one of the best scenes ever made.

1612
01:28:21.670 --> 01:28:24.173
And we used that scene
a lot in <i>High Tension</i>.

1613
01:28:24.340 --> 01:28:30.137
And here it wasn't even like,
you know, like, a conscious reference.

1614
01:28:30.304 --> 01:28:33.182
It was, like, already inside us.

1615
01:28:34.392 --> 01:28:38.062
And all the-- I'm looking at the ax
and I'm thinking about, you know...

1616
01:28:38.229 --> 01:28:40.022
...like, this guy in the souk...

1617
01:28:40.189 --> 01:28:45.444
...who built all the weapon
for the bad guys in Ouarzazate.

1618
01:28:45.653 --> 01:28:49.407
This guy doesn't go to the movies, and
he doesn't know anything about movies.

1619
01:28:49.573 --> 01:28:53.452
So the guy just received
the sketches from Joseph...

1620
01:28:53.619 --> 01:28:55.913
...and then he built that amazing ax.

1621
01:28:56.122 --> 01:28:59.542
DOUG: Please don't kill me.
BIG BRAIN: "Please don't kill me."

1622
01:29:00.584 --> 01:29:03.087
[PLUTO ROARING]

1623
01:29:06.340 --> 01:29:09.885
COMMENTARY: The <i>Excalibur</i> shot,
when he's taking the flag--

1624
01:29:10.094 --> 01:29:12.763
- Out of the--
- Right. Yeah.

1625
01:29:12.930 --> 01:29:14.265
That was a very hard effect.

1626
01:29:14.473 --> 01:29:19.311
That was the most ambitious effect
in the film for prosthetics makeup.

1627
01:29:20.187 --> 01:29:21.647
And we are using, like, a dummy...

1628
01:29:21.814 --> 01:29:24.817
...and we are using the real actor,
and we are using--

1629
01:29:24.984 --> 01:29:28.028
I mean, it's so many different elements
and parameters...

1630
01:29:28.195 --> 01:29:31.449
-...that make the scene possible.
- Also a challenge for the MPAA.

1631
01:29:31.824 --> 01:29:33.742
And also a huge challenge
for the MPAA...

1632
01:29:33.909 --> 01:29:36.370
...because, once again,
I think what disturbed the MPAA...

1633
01:29:36.537 --> 01:29:38.998
...was the fact that everything
looks so real.

1634
01:29:39.165 --> 01:29:42.585
And this shot, it's our tribute
to <i>Straw Dogs</i>, in fact.

1635
01:29:42.751 --> 01:29:47.965
It's funny because during the prep,
we tell to everybody that...

1636
01:29:48.132 --> 01:29:50.968
...that's in the way that we want
to make the movie.

1637
01:29:51.135 --> 01:29:55.389
And because Aaron Stanford
got these glasses for his character--

1638
01:29:55.556 --> 01:29:58.058
We had to have that shot
where he's picking up the glasses...

1639
01:29:58.225 --> 01:30:00.352
...and bringing back the glasses
to his face.

1640
01:30:00.519 --> 01:30:03.731
- Now, this is our-- This is Greg Nicotero.
- This is Greg Nicotero.

1641
01:30:03.898 --> 01:30:06.317
That was-- At the beginning,
we were thinking about, like...

1642
01:30:06.484 --> 01:30:08.319
...using Michael Berryman
for that part.

1643
01:30:08.861 --> 01:30:13.699
And Greg came at the end
and did Cyst.

1644
01:30:13.866 --> 01:30:17.077
It's funny because I think it's the
first time of his life where it's, what...

1645
01:30:17.244 --> 01:30:19.455
...like 100, 120 degrees outside...

1646
01:30:19.622 --> 01:30:22.791
...and he realized what is it
to have so much makeup on your face.

1647
01:30:22.958 --> 01:30:24.793
Exactly.

1648
01:30:24.960 --> 01:30:27.296
- Payback.
- Yeah.

1649
01:30:29.215 --> 01:30:31.967
That's also--
Like, the way he's killing Cyst...

1650
01:30:32.134 --> 01:30:35.095
...came during prep with Aaron,
you know.

1651
01:30:35.262 --> 01:30:37.264
We saw the ax and we were,
like, thinking:

1652
01:30:37.431 --> 01:30:39.767
"That wasn't planned like that."
And we're, "Okay."

1653
01:30:39.934 --> 01:30:42.478
So at that point, Doug mans up...

1654
01:30:42.645 --> 01:30:47.066
...and he's really, like, ready
to become almost vicious.

1655
01:30:47.233 --> 01:30:50.653
So he has to use the pick
of the ax to kill him in the eye.

1656
01:30:50.819 --> 01:30:52.530
That was great.

1657
01:30:52.696 --> 01:30:54.865
And here also, that scene is--

1658
01:30:55.032 --> 01:30:56.867
It's funny because it's working
very well.

1659
01:30:57.034 --> 01:31:00.746
And people like the scene
where the dog is attacking Big Brain.

1660
01:31:00.913 --> 01:31:02.790
But in fact, it was, like, made,
you know--

1661
01:31:02.957 --> 01:31:06.418
We were thinking about,
"Oh, make the scene efficient...

1662
01:31:06.585 --> 01:31:10.130
...without seeing too much of the dog."
Because the dog was a nightmare.

1663
01:31:10.297 --> 01:31:12.174
And it's not the dog
that we used before.

1664
01:31:12.341 --> 01:31:16.136
In fact, it was funny because it was
impossible to have the dogs growling.

1665
01:31:16.303 --> 01:31:21.850
So we asked to the production
to send some dogs from Casablanca...

1666
01:31:22.017 --> 01:31:24.270
...dogs from the military department.

1667
01:31:24.436 --> 01:31:27.064
And he came. The dog came
just to do this shot.

1668
01:31:27.231 --> 01:31:29.858
His close-up. You know,
he came just for his close-up.

1669
01:31:30.025 --> 01:31:35.030
Here you can see a foot
in the stew on the side. It's funny.

1670
01:31:35.197 --> 01:31:38.450
Just, like, part of the body
that we used.

1671
01:31:44.623 --> 01:31:46.542
- That was some real meat.
- Real meat.

1672
01:31:46.709 --> 01:31:48.294
- That was awful.
- That was awful.

1673
01:31:48.460 --> 01:31:50.421
The smell was, like, unbearable.

1674
01:31:53.173 --> 01:31:57.386
And here you can see in the background
some mannequins put in orgy positions.

1675
01:31:58.095 --> 01:32:00.472
- And that was also a big deal.
- Yeah, that was a big deal.

1676
01:32:00.639 --> 01:32:07.021
It was a big deal to make them really,
like, strange and positioned very oddly.

1677
01:32:07.187 --> 01:32:09.356
Lizard's kinky.

1678
01:32:09.523 --> 01:32:13.611
That's also, like, a reminder
of <i>High Tension</i>...

1679
01:32:13.777 --> 01:32:16.947
...with the doll with the missing eye.

1680
01:32:17.156 --> 01:32:19.158
And this is one
of the most creepy shots.

1681
01:32:19.366 --> 01:32:21.243
- Jamison did an amazing job.
- Incredible.

1682
01:32:21.410 --> 01:32:25.122
It's the same process than Ruby, but--

1683
01:32:25.289 --> 01:32:29.043
With the three dots on the face and then
you can change the face as you want.

1684
01:32:29.209 --> 01:32:30.461
But he did an amazing job.

1685
01:32:30.878 --> 01:32:35.591
That was, like, Franklin Vallette, our
first AD's, daughter who played the part.

1686
01:32:35.799 --> 01:32:38.093
- And everyone--
- She's amazing.

1687
01:32:38.260 --> 01:32:40.929
- That creeps people out. That scene is--
- People talk about it.

1688
01:32:41.096 --> 01:32:43.807
- They are talking about that scene.
- It's amazing and it's great.

1689
01:32:43.974 --> 01:32:46.060
It's a wonderful scene.

1690
01:32:46.977 --> 01:32:50.022
He's looking to the hills,
but in fact, the hills are like--

1691
01:32:50.189 --> 01:32:51.874
- There is no hills.
- There is no hills.

1692
01:32:51.940 --> 01:32:55.277
It's like another place, another shot
that the second unit did.

1693
01:32:56.111 --> 01:32:59.573
That's the magic of movies.
It's like, "Wow."

1694
01:32:59.740 --> 01:33:02.868
Everything is possible,
it's just a question of editing.

1695
01:33:10.334 --> 01:33:12.127
BOBBY:
It's okay.

1696
01:33:16.048 --> 01:33:18.175
It's okay. It's okay.

1697
01:33:21.804 --> 01:33:23.389
[BRENDA WHIMPERS]

1698
01:33:24.473 --> 01:33:26.975
COMMENTARY: You can see the
wind behind. That's the real wind.

1699
01:33:27.142 --> 01:33:28.936
- Not a wind machine.
- That's real wind.

1700
01:33:29.103 --> 01:33:31.772
That's the kind of conditions
where we were.

1701
01:33:32.189 --> 01:33:34.858
But that's good
because the sun is shining...

1702
01:33:35.567 --> 01:33:37.194
...which wasn't always the case.

1703
01:33:37.986 --> 01:33:40.364
Sometime with too much wind
and too much sandstorm...

1704
01:33:40.531 --> 01:33:44.535
...you just, you know, lose the light
and everything became overcast.

1705
01:33:44.702 --> 01:33:46.412
And you just cannot shoot.

1706
01:33:46.578 --> 01:33:49.915
But you have to imagine that all the crew
is wearing, like, goggles and stuff...

1707
01:33:50.082 --> 01:33:51.417
...to protect their eyes.

1708
01:33:51.583 --> 01:33:54.712
But the actors, of course,
can't wear those goggles.

1709
01:33:54.878 --> 01:33:56.380
It was very hard.

1710
01:33:56.547 --> 01:33:58.757
The guy who played
the first victim in the opening...

1711
01:33:58.924 --> 01:34:02.136
...during the scientist attack,
gets some sand in his eyes...

1712
01:34:02.302 --> 01:34:04.221
...and he was pretty heavily hurt.

1713
01:34:04.388 --> 01:34:06.515
- He had to go to the hospital.
- Yeah.

1714
01:34:06.682 --> 01:34:08.517
The only one
that had to go to the hospital.

1715
01:34:08.684 --> 01:34:11.311
With the workers in the village.

1716
01:34:11.520 --> 01:34:14.523
Yes, exactly.
Except for the construction workers.

1717
01:34:14.940 --> 01:34:18.360
- But while shooting, anyone injured?
- No. Thanks, God.

1718
01:34:18.527 --> 01:34:20.779
Thanks, God, yeah.
It was really just his eyes.

1719
01:34:23.532 --> 01:34:25.242
BRENDA:
Come on.

1720
01:34:25.409 --> 01:34:27.119
Come on.

1721
01:34:28.662 --> 01:34:31.623
COMMENTARY: Emilie is doing
one of her best performance here...

1722
01:34:31.790 --> 01:34:33.917
...when she's finding
that the body is missing.

1723
01:34:34.084 --> 01:34:36.170
Now, remember, back--
We talked about the scene...

1724
01:34:36.336 --> 01:34:39.882
...but we never, like, being, actually,
like, rehearsed all the scene.

1725
01:34:40.090 --> 01:34:42.259
And she bring that so--

1726
01:34:42.426 --> 01:34:46.555
I mean, so emotional
and so intense way to play it.

1727
01:34:46.722 --> 01:34:51.185
And you really feel the dynamic
between Dan Byrd and her.

1728
01:34:51.351 --> 01:34:56.774
And it works so well
and it's really believable.

1729
01:34:58.484 --> 01:35:02.946
That was also a big challenge because
we were like one hour from the sunset.

1730
01:35:03.155 --> 01:35:05.783
And everything needed
to be shot, like, in one hour.

1731
01:35:05.949 --> 01:35:09.119
- Running out of the light.
- Yeah, running, running against the time.

1732
01:35:10.078 --> 01:35:12.873
But it was that or not--
Or forgetting about that location...

1733
01:35:13.040 --> 01:35:15.083
...which is really, really nice.

1734
01:35:15.250 --> 01:35:19.171
And bring another way, another step
in the evolution of the hills...

1735
01:35:19.338 --> 01:35:22.966
...and in the different kind of rocks.

1736
01:35:24.218 --> 01:35:27.554
Billy Drago. Billy Drago as Jupiter.

1737
01:35:27.721 --> 01:35:32.184
It's amazing because
this guy is so creepy and scary.

1738
01:35:32.726 --> 01:35:34.061
I remember in the casting...

1739
01:35:34.228 --> 01:35:36.814
...having him coming in the room
and we were all scared.

1740
01:35:36.980 --> 01:35:40.150
- He was the only one really scary.
- Yeah. Scary to be in the room with him.

1741
01:35:40.317 --> 01:35:43.278
And he gets so much fun to scare you.
That's also very funny.

1742
01:35:43.445 --> 01:35:45.280
And he's giving you everything.

1743
01:35:45.447 --> 01:35:48.075
I think, really, he believes
so much in movies and stuff...

1744
01:35:48.242 --> 01:35:51.078
...that if you ask him to kill someone
on-screen, I think he'll do it.

1745
01:35:51.245 --> 01:35:52.454
[COMMENTATOR LAUGHING]

1746
01:35:52.621 --> 01:35:55.707
- Yet he is the sweetest man.
- He's the sweetest man, but he really--

1747
01:35:55.874 --> 01:36:00.921
He puts, really, all his person and
all his heart-- Walking and doing so...

1748
01:36:01.088 --> 01:36:03.549
I was worried about
Michael Bailey Smith in that way too.

1749
01:36:03.757 --> 01:36:05.592
If you asked him to kill someone,
he might.

1750
01:36:05.759 --> 01:36:08.303
- Exactly, they are that way.
- They lived their characters.

1751
01:36:08.470 --> 01:36:11.348
Robert Joy is the opposite.
Robert Joy is always taking care of...

1752
01:36:11.807 --> 01:36:14.810
-...you know, his partner.
- Exactly. Definitely.

1753
01:36:15.185 --> 01:36:18.647
That's a great transition.
Because we're outside on location...

1754
01:36:18.814 --> 01:36:21.024
...and then you are inside on-stage.

1755
01:36:21.191 --> 01:36:25.737
And here, you are inside on-stage.
And now you are on location.

1756
01:36:25.904 --> 01:36:28.866
Not even location.
On the backlot of the studio.

1757
01:36:29.074 --> 01:36:32.411
And everything is, like, melded.
And Baxter did an amazing job.

1758
01:36:32.578 --> 01:36:34.246
He did. Baxter is amazing.

1759
01:36:34.413 --> 01:36:38.125
We spent a lot of time in the editing
room, you know, trying to make that.

1760
01:36:38.292 --> 01:36:41.003
And you don't feel any difference.

1761
01:36:41.461 --> 01:36:42.963
It's really good.

1762
01:36:43.171 --> 01:36:45.757
- And that, of course, it's on-stage.
- Stage, a crane shot.

1763
01:36:45.924 --> 01:36:50.429
Above the trailer,
which is impossible to do in real.

1764
01:36:51.138 --> 01:36:53.974
I think that's the only crane shot
that you can find in the movie--

1765
01:36:54.141 --> 01:36:56.977
I mean, in the trailer in the movie.

1766
01:36:58.812 --> 01:37:00.814
- The explosion.
- They were so far away.

1767
01:37:00.981 --> 01:37:04.651
- It doesn't look that way.
- It looks like they are 50 meters away...

1768
01:37:04.818 --> 01:37:06.445
...but in fact, they are like--

1769
01:37:06.612 --> 01:37:10.532
In real life, they needed
like 20 minutes to climb.

1770
01:37:10.699 --> 01:37:14.578
But it's great because
the shot makes the trailer...

1771
01:37:14.745 --> 01:37:18.206
-...really close to them when it explodes.
- Yeah. It looks perfect.

1772
01:37:18.373 --> 01:37:21.919
It looks-- In fact, in a strange way,
it looks like it was made in CG.

1773
01:37:22.085 --> 01:37:25.380
Like you had the explosion behind.
But it's not the case.

1774
01:37:25.589 --> 01:37:29.718
That was really made on set,
on production.

1775
01:37:29.885 --> 01:37:33.263
And it's not so easy to create
a so big explosion with the Airstream...

1776
01:37:33.430 --> 01:37:35.766
...because the Airstream are solid.
You have to precut...

1777
01:37:36.308 --> 01:37:38.602
...all the Airstream in different parts...

1778
01:37:38.977 --> 01:37:43.065
...so everything blow. But you also
have to tie all the pieces with wire...

1779
01:37:43.231 --> 01:37:47.277
...because the pieces can go very,
very far away and hurt someone.

1780
01:37:47.444 --> 01:37:51.031
- Exactly.
- So it was a long prep for that shot.

1781
01:37:51.198 --> 01:37:53.867
We were so lucky also
with the Airstream...

1782
01:37:54.034 --> 01:37:57.955
...because shooting the movie with the
Airstream was one of the first ideas--

1783
01:37:58.163 --> 01:38:03.877
Just to update the trailer of the
Carter family in the original film.

1784
01:38:04.086 --> 01:38:05.545
And to bring some Airstreams...

1785
01:38:05.712 --> 01:38:08.215
...like three or four Airstreams
that we needed to Morocco...

1786
01:38:08.382 --> 01:38:11.051
...was, like, huge and very hard
and we were lucky...

1787
01:38:11.218 --> 01:38:17.015
...to find exact four of the same
Airstreams in Morocco, in Ouarzazate.

1788
01:38:17.182 --> 01:38:19.142
- It's amazing.
- Yeah, that belongs to the king.

1789
01:38:19.309 --> 01:38:22.396
That's right. Exactly.
He liked to vacation in them.

1790
01:38:22.562 --> 01:38:24.314
Yeah, to go hunting.

1791
01:38:27.859 --> 01:38:29.987
I think that day was one of...

1792
01:38:30.153 --> 01:38:32.572
...the worst nightmares
for Maxime Alexandre, our DP...

1793
01:38:32.739 --> 01:38:36.618
...because we started the day,
the fight was in the shadow.

1794
01:38:36.785 --> 01:38:40.163
And then the sun comes out
and they come out, and--

1795
01:38:40.330 --> 01:38:42.624
So it's very hard to shoot it.

1796
01:38:42.791 --> 01:38:48.714
And shadow and sun are, for DP,
you know, like, the enemy...

1797
01:38:48.880 --> 01:38:50.549
...because they can't control them.

1798
01:38:53.635 --> 01:38:55.470
[LIZARD SCREAMS]

1799
01:39:01.309 --> 01:39:04.479
COMMENTARY: Robert Joy and Aaron,
like, rehearsed a lot.

1800
01:39:04.646 --> 01:39:08.567
And we planned to do the fight
with the Aaron body double...

1801
01:39:08.734 --> 01:39:13.947
...and in fact, we used Aaron and he did
it with so much energy and so much--

1802
01:39:14.114 --> 01:39:16.616
It was towards the end of the shooting
and it...

1803
01:39:16.783 --> 01:39:18.243
He was really inside his character.

1804
01:39:18.410 --> 01:39:21.621
Yeah, he was very involved and
he wants to run and do all the stuff.

1805
01:39:21.788 --> 01:39:26.793
And each time when we asked him to do
it again, he was never complaining.

1806
01:39:26.960 --> 01:39:30.338
It's amazing. What he did on that movie
is so intense and so extreme...

1807
01:39:30.505 --> 01:39:34.217
...it's even not acting.
He's really performing something.

1808
01:39:34.384 --> 01:39:36.136
The last two weeks,
it was really all Aaron.

1809
01:39:36.303 --> 01:39:38.013
- Yeah.
- Bloody.

1810
01:39:38.180 --> 01:39:39.514
- Covered with blood.
- Exactly.

1811
01:39:39.681 --> 01:39:42.392
In fact, you know, he was waiting
for that two weeks.

1812
01:39:42.559 --> 01:39:44.019
Since the beginning,
he was waiting.

1813
01:39:44.186 --> 01:39:46.980
He knew that at the end,
he will have to give everything.

1814
01:39:47.147 --> 01:39:48.732
- Right.
- Everything, everything.

1815
01:39:49.691 --> 01:39:56.031
And here, it's really, like, opening
all the doors, all the subconscious stuff.

1816
01:39:56.239 --> 01:39:58.075
And he was like--

1817
01:39:58.241 --> 01:39:59.618
At the beginning, he was like:

1818
01:39:59.785 --> 01:40:01.995
"No, I don't want to yell
too much. I'm not--"

1819
01:40:02.162 --> 01:40:04.372
You know, "I want to keep
that very inside."

1820
01:40:04.539 --> 01:40:08.418
And at the end I really push on him.
And he really, like, gave everything...

1821
01:40:08.585 --> 01:40:11.588
...and it's amazing because he became
in that shot, in that scene...

1822
01:40:12.172 --> 01:40:14.883
...really like the ultimate warrior,
the ultimate beast.

1823
01:40:15.300 --> 01:40:18.261
There is something strange here
that nobody can notice...

1824
01:40:18.428 --> 01:40:20.722
...but all the wall that is behind,
it's a fake wall.

1825
01:40:20.889 --> 01:40:22.766
In fact, we couldn't find this location.

1826
01:40:22.933 --> 01:40:24.309
Yeah, dead end.

1827
01:40:24.476 --> 01:40:27.604
- So to have this dead end on...
- And that's a fake rock.

1828
01:40:27.771 --> 01:40:29.648
And everything is fake.

1829
01:40:29.815 --> 01:40:32.984
Once again, the great work
of Joseph Nemec.

1830
01:40:33.151 --> 01:40:34.694
Yeah, Joseph did an amazing job...

1831
01:40:34.861 --> 01:40:37.614
...because he re-created
the mountain in the mountain.

1832
01:40:37.781 --> 01:40:40.158
And nobody will ever see that...

1833
01:40:40.325 --> 01:40:43.453
...except people that are listening
to us right now...

1834
01:40:43.620 --> 01:40:46.081
...but everything is remade.

1835
01:40:46.248 --> 01:40:48.750
Yeah, and just behind here,
there is a small door...

1836
01:40:48.917 --> 01:40:52.170
...and all the crew was
behind this wall of rock.

1837
01:40:52.337 --> 01:40:54.756
That was funny.
Yeah, like a door in the mountain.

1838
01:40:54.923 --> 01:40:58.218
- Like a secret passage.
- Passageway, yeah.

1839
01:41:00.971 --> 01:41:03.014
We are using the crane here,
and it was so windy...

1840
01:41:03.181 --> 01:41:06.226
...that it was just impossible
to stabilize the shot.

1841
01:41:06.810 --> 01:41:09.312
It was kind of a very hard, hard time.

1842
01:41:09.479 --> 01:41:12.274
And in the same time
we are shooting here in first unit...

1843
01:41:12.440 --> 01:41:16.278
...and Greg is shooting down
in the canyon with second unit...

1844
01:41:16.444 --> 01:41:18.405
...the scene where Bobby is running...

1845
01:41:18.572 --> 01:41:22.450
...and looking for Beauty
in the beginning of the film.

1846
01:41:30.750 --> 01:41:37.090
Once again, the brilliant work of Maisie,
the baby, who's amazing here.

1847
01:41:51.146 --> 01:41:52.898
LIZARD:
Ah!

1848
01:41:53.064 --> 01:41:55.400
COMMENTARY:
That was, like, a very hard shot to do.

1849
01:41:55.901 --> 01:42:01.323
That was a lot of prep for the two
silhouettes, like, falling off the rock.

1850
01:42:01.489 --> 01:42:04.826
That was very important also,
to have that scene.

1851
01:42:09.539 --> 01:42:12.751
The last scene of the film.
I'd almost been fired.

1852
01:42:12.918 --> 01:42:14.044
[COMMENTATORS LAUGHING]

1853
01:42:14.211 --> 01:42:16.855
- That was a hard time.
- That was the beginning of the shooting.

1854
01:42:16.922 --> 01:42:19.007
Not exactly.
That was the beginning of the day.

1855
01:42:19.174 --> 01:42:22.344
I was-- On set,
I was really sick that day...

1856
01:42:22.510 --> 01:42:27.182
...and by like 4 p.m.,
I don't know what's happened...

1857
01:42:27.349 --> 01:42:32.437
...but the sky became so overcast.
That's no light. It went out.

1858
01:42:32.604 --> 01:42:35.273
We were supposed to finish
the scene, finish all that scene...

1859
01:42:35.440 --> 01:42:39.152
...which is the end of the movie,
but it was without light.

1860
01:42:39.319 --> 01:42:43.740
It was, like, so dark.
And everyone became very nervous.

1861
01:42:43.907 --> 01:42:47.911
And it was like
a huge confrontation with you.

1862
01:42:48.078 --> 01:42:49.996
- That's the only one.
- That was the only one.

1863
01:42:50.163 --> 01:42:51.998
That's the only one.

1864
01:42:53.250 --> 01:42:57.087
And we shot the scene
and we didn't use the footage.

1865
01:42:57.254 --> 01:43:00.715
We used that footage, but then,
from there, from that shot...

1866
01:43:00.882 --> 01:43:03.009
...to the end of the film,
we had to come back.

1867
01:43:03.176 --> 01:43:04.552
- We had to reshoot.
- And reshoot.

1868
01:43:04.719 --> 01:43:06.763
Re-create all that. But we left it.

1869
01:43:06.930 --> 01:43:10.392
Yeah, with the blue sky and with the sun
because it's the end of the movie.

1870
01:43:10.558 --> 01:43:12.227
- It's, you know--
- Exactly.

1871
01:43:12.394 --> 01:43:15.522
It has to be positive. It has to be
like they managed to survive.

1872
01:43:15.689 --> 01:43:18.984
They fight so hard, and at the end,
they made it.

1873
01:43:19.150 --> 01:43:23.405
I mean, it's-- You know,
like Doug coming back with the dog.

1874
01:43:23.571 --> 01:43:25.573
It's very triumphalist.

1875
01:43:25.740 --> 01:43:28.326
But we learned a lot
and we made a lot of changes.

1876
01:43:28.493 --> 01:43:29.869
We learned a lot in our rehearsal.

1877
01:43:30.036 --> 01:43:33.540
Yeah, and it's amazing...

1878
01:43:33.707 --> 01:43:36.126
...because the flames
and all the elements...

1879
01:43:36.293 --> 01:43:39.212
...and everyone gathering together,
it's like...

1880
01:43:39.379 --> 01:43:41.381
- The dog.
- It's positive, but in the same time...

1881
01:43:41.548 --> 01:43:44.634
...as the last shot is saying,
you know...

1882
01:43:44.801 --> 01:43:47.887
...it's not because they managed
to survive until now...

1883
01:43:48.054 --> 01:43:50.390
...that they are out of danger...

1884
01:43:50.557 --> 01:43:53.268
...because there is someone else
watching them.

1885
01:43:53.435 --> 01:43:54.936
They're in the middle of the desert.

1886
01:43:55.103 --> 01:43:58.398
They don't have any vehicle,
don't have water, they don't have food.

1887
01:43:58.565 --> 01:44:03.194
So it's another movie
to have them, like--

1888
01:44:03.361 --> 01:44:05.989
Are they going to survive, really?

1889
01:44:29.846 --> 01:44:31.556
And that's the end. That's the end.

1890
01:44:31.723 --> 01:44:33.975
With "In the Valley of the Sun,"
is very positive music.

1891
01:44:34.142 --> 01:44:35.769
With the red...

1892
01:44:35.935 --> 01:44:40.440
And the red crawl, which is like
a reminder of the original picture...

1893
01:44:40.607 --> 01:44:43.485
...and a lot of, you know, like,
films in the '70s.

1894
01:44:43.651 --> 01:44:46.863
You know, we wanted
these very specific, like, things.

1895
01:44:47.030 --> 01:44:50.241
It's funny because right now
they don't do this kind of--

1896
01:44:50.408 --> 01:44:52.427
- End credit. End crawl.
- How they crawling or--

1897
01:44:52.494 --> 01:44:54.704
Yeah, because for TV, they said that--

1898
01:44:54.871 --> 01:44:56.414
- You can't read it.
-"We don't care."

1899
01:44:56.581 --> 01:44:59.292
And we really wanted that.

1900
01:44:59.459 --> 01:45:02.212
- It looks so cool.
- Yeah, yeah, it's really funny.

1901
01:45:02.420 --> 01:45:04.839
- Thanks. I hope you enjoyed this.
- Thanks for joining us.

1902
01:45:05.048 --> 01:45:07.342
I think you enjoyed the film
and you're not too scared.

1903
01:45:07.509 --> 01:45:09.719
- And you understand what we say.
- Enjoy the DVD.

1904
01:45:09.886 --> 01:45:13.848
Yeah, thanks for your patience
with the French accents.

1905
01:48:19.867 --> 01:48:21.869
[ENGLISH SDH]

